column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading at the customer facility, a leak occurred. column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While unloading product at 15100 Oakland Avenue in Highland Park, MI the McKinley Trucking Co., Inc, driver noticed free product releasing from the hose on the cargo tank.  Approximately, fifty gallons of free product released onto a cement pad.  The release was due to a ruptured hose.  Marine Pollution Control of Detroit, Michigan was contacted to perform the cleanup.  Marine Pollution Control used absorbent materials and pads to contain and absorb the free product on the affected cement.  Marine Pollution Control generated 3, 55 gallon recovery drums of diesel fuel contaminated absorbent materials, which were transported back to their facility pending disposal coordination.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  All state and local agencies were notified.  The MSDS was requested and received.
column169: Since the release was due to a ruptured hose, McKinley Trucking Co., Inc. will repair the broken hose and investigate the cause of release to prevent recurrence.

column168: We believe this to be an undeclared hazmat shipment discovered during unloading while the carrier was still present.    A common carrier attempted to deliver 3 pallets containing 32 empty cylinders of Oxyfume 2002 (UN3978) from BOC (Airgas South) in Chattanooga on July 22, 2005.      During unloading Honeywell personnel detected 3 very old cylinders with what appeared to be refrigerant gas valves cleverly positioned in the center of one of the pallets.  The neck labels on the cylinders were totally illegible there were no other hazmat marks or labels on the cylinders to identify the contents.  They were described on the shipping paper as UN3978.    We rejected the cylinders because we were unable to identify the hazardous material contained in them.  They were returned to the original shipper (Airgas South)
column169: Honeywell contacted our sales team via e-mail on July 25, 2005.  The sales manager made the shipper BOC Airgas South aware of the incident.

column168: On 7/20/05 an Eagle driver was delivering to thePantry on 62 Kelly Rd in Fancy Gap, VA. During the unloading he hooked up fittings and started to unlaod when he realized one of the hoses was not properly connected. He spilled approx. 50 gallons of diesel fuel. The diesel flowed across the parking lot to a storm drain. The storm drain discharges to a creek that eventually discharges to the potable water supply for the city of Hillsville. There was no soil impacted. The fire department was called adn they placed absorbent (oil dry) on the pavement and placed a boom around the outfall of the storm drain to contain the spill. Action Environmental contacted Envision Environmental to respond. Envision constructed an underflow dam below  the storm drain outfall and used the boom adn pads to absord the release. They also collected tehabsorbent material and transported it off site for disposal. Envision returned to the site on 7/21/05 and noted only a small sheen near the discharge. they removed the absorbents and indicated that no further action is required. The release did not affect any of the discharges connected.
column169: Better training in unloading procedures

ERS of Ohio, Inc. was contacted to coordinate disposal.

column168: On July 1, 2005 an Onyx employee was loading drums into a trailer at the Onyx 10-day intransit facility located in Latham, NY. While loading a drum, it was discovered that a 55-gallon drum containing a nitric acid/chromium mixture was leaking. Approximately 20 gallons of the material had leaked through a hole in the bottom of the drum onto the floor of the trailer. The leaking drum was overpacked into a 95-gallon drum. The material that had leaked onto the floor of the trailer was cleaned up with speedi-dry and absorbant pads. The cleanup materials were placed into a 55-gallon drum for disposal.
column169: It was determined this spill was caused due to a faulty drum cart. The drum cart was old and the metal forks on the bottom of the drum cart were sharp and protruding upward. When this drum cart was used to grab and move this drum, it's metal forks punctured the bottom of the drum resulting in a spill of the drums' contents.   This drum cart was put "out of service" immediately and was disgarded a week later.  As a result of this incident, drum carts are inspected daily at the Latham, NY intransit facility. A more comprehensive training of the proper use and inspection of drum carts has been implemented to help prevent recurrences of this type of incident.

column168: Shipment was apparently loaded at origin with an inadequate amount of fill freight or dunnage to block drums from moving.  Drums shifted off skid while in transit and one drum rubbed against rough metal on another shipment.  Metal punctured plastic drum in two places and released approximately one half gallon of contents.  Spill was contained and cleaned up at unloading facility.  Damaged drum was taken to haz mat bay to await disposition from shipper.  Remainder of shipment sent on to destination.
column169: Drums were shrink wrapped on to skid.  Having the drums strapped to the skid would secure drums to skid better.  Loading facility should have filled gaps between freight and used adequate dunnage to keep metal away from drums.  Notice sent to loading facility to review loading practices and use of dunnage.

column168: Driver left his work facility (Morrisville, PA) at 5:30 a.m. and arrived at his first stop in Millville, NJ at approximately 7:45 a.m..  When the driver opened his trailer door to enter he noticed a smell of mineral spirits.  The driver made the delivery and proceeded to investigate the odor.  He found a leaking tote in the front right corner of the trailer.  The 22" dome lid on a stainless steel tote loosened and partially came off during transit.  Approximately 2-3 gallons of material leaked onto the trailer floor and quickly evaporated.  The driver contacted his supervisor who came to his aid with a new gasket, lid and retaining ring.  The new parts replaced the old parts and the driver completed the rest of his deliveries without incident.
column169: Reinforcing the current operating procedure will be addressed.  A through check of the defective tote would have discovered the loose fitting part.  A simple tightening down or replacement of the parts in question would have prevented the spill.

column168: PLCX 129050 LOADED METHANOL TANK CAR WAS NOTICED BY A CSX CAR INSPECTOR TO HAVE PRODUCT COMING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR.  A CSX HAZMAT SENTINEL WAS DISPATCHED, INVESTIGATE AND PLACED A BUCKET UNDER THE DRIP TO CONTAIN THE PRODUCT.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PRODUCT LEAK WAS COMING FROM THE LIQUID LINE.  A CSX HAZMAT CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO HANDLE CONTAINMENT AND CONTROL OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE HAZMAT SENTINEL AND THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THE LIQUID LINE WAS DRIPPING PRODUCT BETWEEN THE VALVE SEAT AND THE PIPE NIPPLE.  THE CONTRACTOR TIGHTENED THE VALVE BODY 1 1/2 TURNS, THE LEAK STOPPED.  PLCX 129050 WAS STAGED FOR 8 HOURS AND NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED.  PLCX 129050 WAS RELEASED AND FORWARDED FOR DISPOSITION TO CONSIGNEE.    NARRI 5(5+3+0) (3+0) = 120  CAUSE CODE = 538

column169: This is the 3rd related incident with Enterprise Trucking loading the same product with the same PRV failure but on different trailers. Carriers must ensure through an effective PM program/testing methodologies that trailers are servicable before each transportation of a hazardous material.

column168: While unloading freight from trailer material handler discovered a drum that was leaking from the bung closure. column168: Driver was delivering a load of gasoline and diesel in Augusta, GA.  Customer was supposed to receive 2500 gallons of gas and 5000 gallons of diesel.  Dispatch entered the qrong quantities.  Our driver took 5000 gallons of gas and 2500 gallons of diesel to the location.  Our driver had someone that worked for APEC sign our product integegrity sheet.  This document is supposed to keep us from pumping product into a tank that will not hold what we deliver.  The person that signed this sheet did not know what she was doing.  After our driver pumped 4000 gallons of gas into the tank, it spilled approximately 50 gallons out the top of the tank because it could not hold anymore.
column169: When delivering to a customer that has an above ground tank, we will have two people verify the quantities, then we will dispatch the load.  We have also made a recomendation to the customer to print the capacity on the side of the tank along with directions on how to read the meter.

column168: According to the information obtained the following occurred.  While unloading, one, three hundred gallon plastic tote was discovered leaking.  Approximately, two hundred and twenty gallons of free product were released.  The release was due damaging the ball valve while unloading.  The Pasco City Fire Department responded to the scene.  NRC Environmental of Portland, Oregon was contacted to perform the cleanup.  NRC Environmental performed the cleanup using absorbent materials, booms and pads.  NRC Environmental excavated the contaminated soil.  NRC Environmental will coordinate disposal of all waste generated.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.

column168: FILE-05-226 DOT SHIPPER-MAGNETO POWER AWB#-DAL 87505450885 HRL  ON 07/23/2005 AT 0217, A LEAKING AND ODOROUS SHIPMENT WAS REPORTED IN "B" BUILDING OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  SPILL TECHNICIANS RONNIE HUFF AND MATTHEW PHILLIPS DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND EMITTING AN ODOR.  THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION, THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO BE A FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINING 12 - 16 OUNCE METAL AEROSOL CANS OF CARB/CHOKE CLEANER.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS MARKED AS A CONSUMER COMMODITY, ORMD.  DUE TO A FAULTY SEAM ON THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE AEROSOL CANS, 12 OUNCES OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT #404, N767AX.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY DECLARED AS A CONSUMER COMMODITY, ORMD WITH THE CORRECT MARKINGS/LABELS, BUT WAS MISSING THE SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0328.  THERE ARE PICTURES IN FILE IN THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

An operator was loading CHVX-288014 Styrene tankcar.  The operator was inspecting the tank car during loading.  The tank car was overloaded and spilled over.  The operator got some sytrene on hisself.  Operator shut down loading.  Operator received 1st aid treatment.Operator checked tank car loading meter.  Meter had setting of 185,000 lb.  Operator thought he put in 171,000 lb.  This tank car couldn't take 185,000lb.  Calculated 1600 lb spilled out tank car.  Majority went into secondry containment.  Rest was recovered with absorbent blanket.  Duration of overflow was about one minute.  The spilled material was pumped to slop oil tankage.  Material picked up with absorbent blanket was put into drums.   Material that got on soil was picked up and put into waste dumpster.

column168: THE DRIVER CONNECTED THE DOWNSPOUT FITTING TO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK THEN PULLED HIS PRODUCT DELIVERY HOSE AND CONNECTED IT TO THE DOWNSPOUT, HOWEVER HE NEGLECTED TO SECURE THE KAMLOCK LEVERS.  WHEN HE OPENED HIS DELIVERY VALVE THE HOSE DISCONNECTED FROM THE DOWNSPOUT RELEASING PRODUCT TO THE CEMENT PAD.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE DELIVERY VALVE AND BEGAN CONTAINMENT PROCEDURES.  ONCE CONTAINED, HE CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND OUR DISPATCH CENTER.  OUR DISPATCH CENTER SENT OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  TOTAL CLEAN UP COMPLETED BY 15:00 HRS.

column168: THE DRIVER MISGAUGED THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK CAPACITY AND ATTEMPTED TO UNLOAD MORE THAN THE TANK COULD HOLD.  WHEN THE TANK STOPPED ACCEPTING PRODUCT BECUASE THE OVERFLOW VALVE CLOSED THE DRIVER CLOSED THE VALVE FROM HIS TRUCK.  HE CLEARED HE DELIVERY HOSE, HOWEVER THIS PUT PRESSURE ON THE STORAGE TANK AND AT THE FINAL DISCONNECTION THE TANK BURPED BACK PRODUCT THAT SPLASHED TO THE TARMAC.  THE DRIVER ATTEMPTED HIS BEST TO PREVENT PRODUCT FROM ENTERING THE STORM DRAIN BUT WAS NOT COMPLETELY SUCCESSFUL.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND OUR DISPATCH DEPARTMENT.  IN TURN OUR DISPATCH DEPARTMENT NOTIFIED OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM AND OUR CLEAN-UP CONTRACTORS.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CALLED SAN MATEO COUNTY HEALTH DEPARTMENT.  TOTAL CLEAN UP WAS COMPLETED BY 14:00 HRS.
column169: A DETAILED ANALYSIS THAT ADDRESSES THE ROOT CAUSE OF THIS INCIDENT WILL BE SHARED WITH ALL OUR DRIVERS THRU SAFETY BULLETINS, TAILGATE MEETINGS AND DURING OUR NEXT ROUND OF SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: The release occurred while transferring asphalt cement from a tanker truck into two above-ground storage tanks. The release occurred at approximately 0615 on 07/07/2005. A tanker truck containing asphalt cement was discharging its contents into a 100-gallon holding tank that pumps the asphalt cement into two 32,500-gallon above-ground storage tanks. The pump inside the holding tank failed due to an electrical surge. This caused the holding tank to overflow approximately 300-gallons of asphalt cement. At the time of the release, the driver of the tanker truck was approximately 20 feet from the tanker truck shutoff valve. The driver of the tanker truck immediately became aware of the release and turned off the flow of asphalt cement from the tanker truck. The duration of the release is unknown.     The area of the release was paved with asphalt and no soil was affected.    After the flow of asphalt cement shutoff, it was allowed to cool then scooped up with shovels and stockpiled onsite. The stockpiled asphalt cement will be reused to produce asphalt at a later date.
column169: A set of driver rules was developed and immediately implemented.    1. Drivers must follow designated routes to loading/unloading racks and control rooms.  2. Drivers must remain with their trucks and out of the truck cab during loading/unloading operations.  3. Drivers must close loading/unloading valves prior to leaving the rack.  4. Drivers must wear personal protective equipment during loading and unloading operations.  5. Drivers must wear a face-shield in the down position during loading/unloading operations.

column168: The shipment was offered under a vessel sharing agreement to Hapag-Lloyd Container Line by OOCL Lines, on behalf of their shipper, for transport on the Hapag-Lloyd container vessel Paris Express from Savannah, Georgia to Singapore.    The shipment was declared as: RQ, Chromium Trioxide, Anhydrous, 5.1, UN 1463.     OOCL advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed from Savannah, that the fright container in fact contained: RQ, Oxidizing Solid, Corrosive, N.O.S. (Contains Chromic Acid), 5.1, UN 3085.    The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not reflect the correct hazardous material loaded in the container.    OOCL subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd.

column168: A loaded hopper railcar had been moved from Track 4 to Track 3 and coupled to a secure line of railcars.  Loaded railcars were being moved on Track 4 toward the switch for Tracks 3 & 4.  The railcar placed on Track 3 became uncoupled and rolled toward the Track 3/4 switch, as the railcars on Track 4 were approaching.  The unsecured Track 3 railcar contacted two of the railcars on Track 4 and caused a derailment of all cars.  The railcar on Track 3 rolled over and released 2500 pounds of product through a dislodged top man-way.  Both railcars on Track 4 remained upright with one railcar receiving a large puncture on the side of the tank shell releasing 100 pounds of product.  The material released was solid crystal and stopped after the railcars came to rest.  The material was recovered with shovels, buckets, and heavy equipment and returned to the processing area of the plant.  The railcars were re-railed, off-loaded of product, and sent to Union Tank Car for repair.
column169: Improved operating procedures will be immediately employed.  First, the brakes will be set on all lead railcars on any lineup of railcars.  Second, a spotter will be used to ensure a clear track is available at all times of railcar movement.  Third, railcar operators will be retrained on using practices to verify coupling of railcars (i.e. 'pull-back' after engagement, etc.).
column172: Rail hopper car for solid materials only

column168: The shipment was booked with Hapag-Lloyd for two items of hazardous material - Toluene, Class 3, UN 1294, and RQ, Trichloroethylene Class 6.1, UN 1710 - for loading under a under a vessel sharing agreement on the P & O Nedlloyd Container Line vessel PONL Sydney from New York to Southampton, UK.       The shipper advised Hapag-Lloyd after the vessel had sailed that in addition to the two items originally booked, Methyl Methacrylate, Monomer, Stabilized, Class 3, UN 1247, was also loaded in the freight container.       The shipping papers that accompanied the freight container to the marine terminal did not reflect the additional hazardous material.    The shipper subsequently provided corrected hazardous material shipping papers to Hapag-Lloyd, and P & O Nedlloyd was advised of the undeclared hazardous material.

column168: A chlorine leak was reported by Borden & Remington to Pioneer on July 15th at 8:13 AM. The leak was discovered at their site before starting the unloading operation. The rail car was still temporary storage. The rail car contained 180 000 lbs of chlorine at the time of reporting.    Pioneer sent Hazmat trained personnel to help Borden & Remington personnel handle the situation. It was uncovered that the leak was coming underneath the flange of the right vapor angle valve as per chlorine manufacturer terminology.    An emergency C-kit was applied to mitigate the leak.    In the following days, Borden & Remington proceeded with the unloading of the chlorine rail car. Once the transfer was completed, Pioneer sent, to the rail car location, a Pioneer representative along with an emergency contractor to degas the chlorine rail car in a diluted solution of sodium hydroxide and purge it with nitrogen. As a precaution, the vapor valve was replaced with a new one. This operation took place on August 3rd and August 4th. No leakage was experienced during the tank car clean up.    During the clean up operation, a visual inspection of the dome plate and the valve was performed. The gas valve was in excellent conditions. However, the gasket grooves located on the pressure plate showed damage in 2 specific areas. The thickness of the grooves was less in these specific areas. It is believe that an impact on the grooves during the valve installation or gasket removal could be at the source of the problem.
column169: In light of the observations, Pioneer is proceeding in providing refresher training on valve installation, valve maintenance and gasket removal procedures to the chlorine operators involved in these operations. Our internal procedures do include a mention on the importance of using proper tools such as a brass screwdriver and not a metal screwdriver in order to prevent impact or gouge on the grooves.

column168: While stopped at a truck stop in Porter, IN, the driver noted a leak of material coming from the trailer.  He immediately called for a spill response crew.  Within 2 hours the spill cleanup crew was on site.  Upon arrival to the site the crew found one steel 55 gallon drum with an abrasion in the side.  The steel material had been completely rubbed away and a whole was created.  A small amount of the Syltherm XLT Heat Transfer fluid had been released on to the trailer floor.  The damaged drum was overpacked into a salvage drum and re-palletized for further shipment.  The liquid on the trailer floor was absorbed with granular sorbents.  This material was then swept up and placed into a drum for proper disposal. The entire process of response and spill clean up took approximately 6 hours.
column169: Our recommentdation would be to have the shipper check all pallets and drums prior to shipment.  This will allow any problems to be spotted prior to movement of the material.  In addition, drums should be loaded to the pallet in a manner as to prevent abrasion/friction during transportation.

column168: HIDDEN HAZ MAT/DGR FOUND. LOCAL FAA INSPECTED AND DETERMINED THAT BATTERY ACID WAS A HIDDEN HAZ MAT. OTHER ITEMS FOUND : gasoline engine with no gas and car type battery. Shipment was missing all hazard labels ( corrosive, arrow labels) and Shipper's declaration for Dangerous Goods. The shipper was advised to correct errors and provide corrective action. The shipment was picked up from Lufthansa Cargo and the forwardering agent advised it would be transported via ocean to destination .
column169: The shipper was advised to take corrective actions. At first the shipper hired a Hazmat company (HMX) to correct errors and remove the battery acid. We asked that written corrective action be given before we sent the shipment. We recommended checking with suppliers if hazardous material would be sent as the shipper said he did not see the cargo. This was only discussed we did not get any written corrective action from the shipper.   The forwarding agent ( Salines, Dallas, Tx. Joe-214-630-2888) was also advised to advise us of corrective action and submit in writing. Corrective action was dicsussed but we did not get written corrective action. We would not forward until corrective action was received, then the shipment was picked up and as per shipper would be transported via ocean not air.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 18:30 ON JULY 1ST 2005, TWO TRIUMVIRATE EMPLOYEES NOTICED A GREENISH LIQUID DRIPPING FROM ONE OF OUR PARTIALLY LOADED HAZMAT VEHICLES PARKED IN OUR SECURE TRANSPORTATION FACILITY YARD.  THE EMPLOYEES IMMEDIATLEY PLACED ABSORBENT MATERIAL ONTO THE EFFECTED ASPHALT, WHILE AT THE SAME TIME PLACING A PLASTIC BUCKET BENEATH THE DRIP.  THE LIQUID PH WAS DETERMINED TO BE NEUTRAL.  THE LIQUID WAS ALSO DETERMINED NOT TO BE AN OXIDIZER.  AFTER TAKING THE IMMEDIATE STEPS TO CONTROL THE SPREAD OF THE RELEASE, THE EMPLOYEES REVIEWED THE HAZMAT SHIPPING PAPERS AND DETERMINED THE MOST LIKELY SOURCE FOR THE LEAK AS BEING ONE OR MORE CONTAINERS OFFERED BY A PARTICULAR SHIPPER.  AT 19:38 THE TWO EMPLOYEES, USING SUPPLIED-AIR RESPIRATORS, APPROPRIATE AIR MONITORING EQUIPMENT, AND APPROPRIATE PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT, ENTERED THE REAR OF THE VEHICLE TO IDENTIFY AND CONTAIN THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK.  AFTER ONLY A FEW MINUTES THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS FOUND.  THE LEAK WAS SEEN TO BE FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM, ALONGSIDE THE BOTTOM SEAM.  NEXT, THE LEAKING CONTAINER WAS PROPERLY PLACED INTO A STEEL 85 1A2 SALVAGE DRUM.  AFTER THE LEAKING DRUM WAS CONTROLLED, THE EMPLOYEES CLEANED UP THE SPILL RESIDUE AND DECONTAMINATED THE TRUCK FLOOR AND THE IMPACTED ASPHALT SURFACE.  THESE CLEANUP BY-PRODUCTS WERE THEN PROPERLY MANAGED FOR DISPOSAL AS WASTES.
column169: FROM OUR AFTER-INCIDENT REVIEW, TRIUMVIRATE WAS ABLE TO DETERMINE THAT THE MOST LIKELY CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS RELATED TO THE MANNER IN WHICH THIS PARTICULAR CONTAINER HAD BEEN STORED AT THE GENERATOR/SHIPPER SITE.  OUR ONSITE INSPECTION REVELAED THAT THIS CONTAINER HAD BEEN INADVERTANTLY STORED IN DIRECT CONTACT WITH ACCUMULATED LIQUIDS THAT APPEAR TO HAVE DETERIORATED THE INTEGRITY OF THE CONTAINER AND CONTRIBUTED TO THE SUBSEQUENT LEAK.  THE SHIPPER AGREED TO PURCHASE AND INSTALL CHEMICALLY RESISTANT STORAGE PALLETS TO PREVENT THE RISK OF DRUM: LIQUID CONTACT IN THE FUTURE.  THEY HAVE ALSO AGREED TO ADDRESS AND MITIGATE THE SOURCE OF THE LIQUID IN WHICH THE DRUMS SAT, AND TO CONTINUE TO CLOSELY INSPECT THE CONTAINERS FOR LEAKS AT THE TIME THEY ARE OFFERED FOR SHIPMENT.

column168: THE CAR SHOP AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN AVON, IN REPORTED THAT FRA INSPECTOR GILMORE HAD DISCOVERED THAT TANK CAR, UTLX 72729, LOAD COMBUSTIBLE LIQUID, NOS (COAL TAR) HAD A SPLASH LEAK AT THE TOP OF THE CAR WHEN IT WAS MOVED.  THE CAR WAS LOCATED IN THE #1 CLASS TRACK.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  THE SHIPPER, ABC COKE, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT VIA CHEMTREC.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET HAD A 2 INCH SECTION MISSING WHICH ALLOWED THE PRODUCT TO SLOSH OUT FROM THE MANWAY COVER WHEN THE CAR WAS MOVED.  IT WAS ESTIMATED 1 QUART OR LESS OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN RELEASED.  THE CONTRACTOR DID NOT HAVE A REPLACEMENT GASKET ON HAND.  A TEMPORARY TEFLON ROPE GASKET WAS INSTALLED UNTIL A REPLACE GASKET WAS MADE.  ON 07/20/2005, THE CONTRACTOR RETURNED AND INSTALLED A NEW MANWAY COVER GASKET, SECURED THE CAR AND RELEASED IT.  ABC COKE WAS ADVISED AS TO THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While at the Triple Crown Service's facility in Sandusky, Ohio free product was discovered leaking from a trailer.  The Sandusky Fire Department, Erie County Hazmat Team and Erie County Fire Department responded to the scene to assess the site.  The Sandusky Fire Department placed absorbent material in the trailer to contain and absorb the free product.  E.R.S. of Bowling Green, Ohio was contacted to perform the cleanup.  E.R.S placed additional absorbent materials on the affected area.  The cleanup materials were placed into 2, fifty-five gallon recovery drums which were transported back to their facility in Bowling Green, OH pending disposal coordination.  No injuries or exposures were reported.  The MSDS was requested and received.  All state and local agencies were notified.
column169: Since the release was accidental and due to leak on the weld seam of the container, no plans currently exist to prevent recurrence.

While stopped at a truck stop the driver noted a small leak coming from the trailer.  He immediately called for a clean up crew.  Upon arrival to the site the ER crew found two 55-gallon poly drums with loose bungs.  The Syltherm XLT material had apparently leaked through the loose seals due to the jarring during transportation.  Approximately 8-9 gallons of material was spilled on to the trailer floor.  The ER crew tightened the bungs on all drums present to ensure that no further leaks would occur.  The liquid on the trailer floor was absorbed using granular sorbents.  This material was then swept up and placed into a drum for proper disposal.  The entire process of response and clean up took approximately four hours.
column169: We recommend that the shipper check all drums prior to shipment for tightend closures and appropriate packaging on the trailer.

During unloading an 80 Gallon stainless steel tank, that had been loaded onto a load rack, had fallen over onto other freight. A haz mat response team was called in to clean up spill. Upon arrival they were shown a puddle of product in front of two loading dock doors on the concrete drive. The puddle was covering an area 4 to 5 feet wide by 30 feet long. The trailer was empty and the floor appeared to be damp from the product. Some of the product had seeped through the floor but most of it had run out the back of the trailer onto the concrete. Absorbent material was utilized to clean up all of the free liquids. A neutralization solution was sprayed on the concrete, the inside and the outside of the trailer. It was allowed to neutralize for 30 minutes prior to additional absorbent being placed down to remove all free liquids. Upon inspection of the tank it was found that it was an 80 gallon tank with 36 gallons of product actually shipped (excess product). It is estimated that 8 to 10 gallons of product spilled. When it tipped over the product was released from the bung cap. The bung cap had only been hand tight and the O-Ring seal was broken. The outside of the tank was neutralized and cleaned. One 55 gallon drum of waste was generated and taken off site to Environmental Management. The tank and remaining product were also removed by Environmental Management. Since the tank was not damaged no claim will be filed against Watkins.

column168: AT 16:30 ON 7/6/05 A SULFURIC ACID TANK TRUCK WAS PARTIALLY UNLOADED INTO THE STORAGE TANK, 540-T.  THE CONTROL SYSTEM AUTOMATICALLY STOPPED THE TRUCK UNLOAD WHEN IT DETECTED THAT 540-T WAS FULL.  THE PLANT OPERATIONS TEAM TRANSFERRED SOME LEVEL OUT OF 540-T TO ALLOW FOR THE EMPTYING OF THE TANK TRUCK.  WHEN FLOW FROM THE TANK TRUCK WAS RE-ESTABLISHED APPROXIMATELY 30 LBS OF SULFURIC ACID SPILLED FROM THE 540-T VENT LINE, LOCATED NEXT TO THE TRUCK UNLOAD AREA.  THE SPILL WAS STOPPED WITHIN 1 MINUTE BY CLOSING THE UNLOADING AUTO BLOCK VALVE.  IT WAS LATER DETERMINED THAT THE N2 REGULATOR FOR UNLOADING HAD FAILED.
column169: THE ORDER QUANTITY FOR SULFURIC TRUCKS HAS BEEN REDUCED FROM 23 TONS TO 20 TONS.  THE NITROGEN REGULATOR USED TO PRESSURIZE TANKERS FOR UNLOADING HAS BEEN REPLACED.  CONSIDERATION IS BEING GIVEN TO THE FOLLOWING ACTIONS (1) INSTALL AN AUTO-BLOCK VALVE IN THE N2 LINE WHICH WILL CLOSE WHEN THE TRUCK IS NOT UNLOADING.  (2) RE-ROUTE THE VENT LINE FROM 540-T TO A SAFER LOCATION.

column168: July 22, 2005 - Heil cargo tank is filled in prepartation for 07/26/05 delivery to Von Roll, East Liverpool, OH. Delivery date postponed until 08/01/05. Cargo tank parked on gravel parking lot.  July 23, 2005 - As per standard operating procedure, Heil cargo tank visually examined and found to be ok.  July 25, 2005 - Heil cargo tank visually examined, indications of spillage were found on the ground.  Estimated that approximately 10 gallons were spilled.  Pre-trip analytical results were cansulted and no RQ values were exceeded. It was determined a combination of high ambient temperatures, the nature of the load, and the slight incline upon which the tanker was parked caused failure of a PVC cap on a fitting at the rear hatch of the tanker.  The Schedule 80 PVC fittings, including the plug, vertical pipe section and the flange were also compromised.  They were soft and    pliable, with ripples in the plug threading and a tear where the leak began. The cargo tank was moved and 15 yd3 of soil was removed from the affected area as quickly as possible.  A backhoe was brought in to facilitate soil removal.   Analytical samples of the contaminated soil were taken and sent to an off-site lab to confirm that RQ values were not exceeded.  All contaminated soil will be disposed of in an environmentally correct manner. The hole was then filled with course aggregate (to indicate the depth of excavation should further examination be necessary) followed by top gravel.  July 26 - All PVC fittings on the Heil Cargo tank were replaced with chemical-resistant coated steel or stainless steel fittings.
column169: - All PVC fittings on the Heil Cargo tank were replaced with chemical-resistant coated steel or stainless steel fittings.  - All loaded vehicles in the transportation cycle will be parked on the concrete pad.    - A specific cargo tank parking area, complete with it’s own secondary containment, is being designed and will be built as soon as feasible.

column168: DRIVER FAILED TO MAKE A SLIGHT RIGHT HAND TURN AND WENT OFF THE ROADWAY AND OVERTURNED.  THE TRAILER BECAME ENGULFED IN FLAMES AND COMPLETELY BURNED.  ALL PRODUCT ON THE TRAILER WAS EITHER CONSUMED OR RELEASED.  A MAJORITY OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONSUMED BY THE FIRE.  THE ACCIDENT WAS FATAL TO OUR DRIVER.  WE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN-UP CONTRACTOR MIDWEST ENVIORNMENTAL SERVICES TO MITIGATE THIS LOSS, BUT THERE WAS LITTLE THEY COULD DO INITIALLY, AS THE FIRE DEPT LET THE FIRE BURN OUT. column169: DRIVER ARE CONTINUALLY COUNSELED AND INSTRUCTED ON THE SAFE OPERATION OF OUR TRUCKS/TRAILERS.  TOPICS SUCH AS SPEED AND TURN NEGOTIATION ARE SOME OF THE ITEMS DISCUSSED REGULARLY AT OUR SAFETY MEETINGS.

column168: BNSF CAR FOREMAN REPORTED A HISSING NOISE AUDIBLE FROM GROUND LEVEL EMANATING FROM TOP OF GATX 83631.  GATX 83631 WAS STANDING ON A REPAIR TRACK AWAITING TRUCK SIDE BEARING REPAIR.  BNSF RESPONDERS INVESTIGATING, REPORTED VAPOR LEAK SOURCE AS THE 280.5 SAFETY RELIEF VALVE (SRV).  GATX 83631 SIDE STENCIL INDICATED THAT THIS VALVE WAS TESTED IN 2004-MRN AND DUE FOR RETEST IN 2009.  RESPONDERS CONCLUDED THAT THE SRV O-RINGS COULD POSSIBLY BE THE CAUSE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE AND ATTEMPTED TO REPAIR.  DURING THE INITIAL REPAIR ATTEMPT THE BODY ASSEMBLY WAS LOOSENED AND LIFTED.  THIS RESULTED IN A INCREASED SRV RELEASE AND RESPONDERS QUICKLY REPLACED THE SRV, SUSPECTING THAT THE SRV WAS DEFECTIVE BEYOND THE O-RING PROGNOSIS.  GATX 83631 WAS MOVED TO A LPG UNLOADING FACILITY AT BARSTOW AND SHIPPER MADE ARRANGEMENTS TO OFF LOAD ALL PRODUCT FROM GATX 83631.  AFTERWARDS GATX 83631 WAS PURGED AND FORWARDED TO THE GATX RAIL REPAIR FACILITY IN COLTON, CA FOR SRV REPAIR OR REPLACEMENT.
column169: PENDING INVESITGATION INTO THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE RELEASE.

column168: TANK CONTAINER BAFU 888247 (PARKED IN THE BNSF INTERMODAL PARKING LOT) WAS REPORTED BY INTERMODAL HUB DRIVER THAT IT WAS EMANATING PRODUCT ODOR.  AREA AROUND BAFU 888247 WAS CORDONED OFF.  CONTRACT RESPONDERS WERE CALLED, BUT THE BNSF HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RESPONDER ARRIVED AND TOOK CHARGE.  BNSF RESPONDER DETERMINED THAT ONE MANWAY WAS THE CULPRIT SOURCE OF THE PRODUCT ODOR.  THIS FOUR BOLT MANWAY LID HAD ITS BOLTS TIGHT WITH THE TEFLON GASKET IN GOOD SHAPE.  THE MANWAY LID HAD A LITTLE PLAY AT THE HINGE AREA AND WHEN IT WAS ORIGINALLY CLOSED, THE LID DID NOT MATCH UP TO THE MANWAY GASKET GROOVE.  BNSF RESPONDER REPOSITIONED THE MANWAY LID AND RESECURED THE MANWAY BY 2220 HRS. CDT, 7/28; AND NO FURTHER PRODUCT ODOR WAS EVIDENT AFTER THIS SECUREMENT WAS COMPLETED.  CONTRACT RESPONDER WAS DISMISSED PRIOR TO FULL MOBILIZATION OF THEIR RESPONSE TEAM.

column168: THE PACKAGE WAS DROPPED IN HANDLING.  EXAMINATION OF THE INNER CONTAINER REVEALED A RUPTURED SEAM WHICH ALLOWED THE CONTENTS TO ESCAPE.  THE LEAKAGE WAS CONTAINED.  THE UNDAMAGED PORTION OF THE PACKAGE WAS REPACKED FOR RETURN TO SHIPPER.

MIKE BABANATS DISCOVERED THE PACKAGE WHEN IT WAS SITTING, BUSTED OPEN.  OUTSIDE A FEEDER, GOING TO TAPE UP THE BOX, MIKE NOTICED THAT A BOX INSIDE HAD A FLAMMABLE LIQUID LABEL ON IT.  AN MSDS WAS OBTAINED, AND SHOWED THAT THE PRODUCT INSIDE WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THERE WERE NO SHIPPING PAPER OR ANYTHING ELSE THAT INDICATED THAT THE CONTENTS WERE HAZARDOUS.

I WAS NOTIFIED BY PHONE OF A FLAMMABLE LIQUID SPILL IN THE FACILITY.  I RESPONDED WITH THE APPROPRIATE PPE, (GOGGLES, GLOVES, BOOTS AND APRON).  SCBA WAS NOT NECESSARY.  I CONTAINED THE SPILL, DECONTAMINATED THE AREA, AND BROUGHT THE DAMAGED MATERIALS TO THE DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  FOLLOWING MY DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET, I DISPOSED OF THE WASTE THROUGH THE DMP.  THERE WAS NO SALVAGEABLE PORTION OF THE PRODUCT.

ON 07/23/05 OUR DRIVER WAS CROSSING THE RAILROAD TRACKS AT 31ST ST SW IN BIRMINGHAM, AL WHEN THE RIGHT REAR PORTION OF OUR TRAILER WAS STRUCK BY A CSX TRAIN.  THIS CAUSED THE TANK TO RUPTURE AND SPILL JET FUEL.  THE FORCE OF THE IMPACT FORCED OUR TRACTOR/TRAILER OFF THE ROADWAY INTO A CULVERT WHERE ANOTHER GOUGE WAS PUT INTO THE TANK ALLOWING MORE FUEL TO ESCAPE.  EMERGENCY PERSONNEL WERE IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED IN ADDITION TO SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES TO HANDLE THE CLEAN-UP EFFORTS.  THE JET FUEL THAT WAS REMAINING IN THE TRAILER WAS QUICKLY PUMPED OUT TO AVOID ANY FURTHER RELEASE.  THE CROSSING WHERE THIS ACCIDENT OCCURRED IS NOT GATED AND THERE ARE REPORTS THAT THE FLASHING LIGHTS WERE NOT OPERATING PROPERLY.
column169: DRIVERS WILL BE COUNSELED AND RE-EDUCATED ON THE STEPS THAT MUST BE TAKEN IN ORDER TO SAFELY CROSS RAILROAD TRACKS.

column168: THE DRIVER FOR CTL DISTRIBUTION ARRIVED AT GOLD COAST LINEN TO DELIVER 1,800 GALLONS OF STARLITE LAUNDRY BUILDER, WHICH WAS A PARTIAL LOAD WITH THE BALANCE OF THE PRODUCT BEING DELIVERED TO ANOTHER LOCATION.  THE CUSTOMER AT GOLD COAST LINEN WAS UNABLE TO VERIFY THEIR TANK LEVEL.  THE GAUGE ON THE CUSTOMER TANK WAS NOT WORKING ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER.  THE CUSTOMER'S TANK WAS NOT VISIBLE FROM THE UNLOADING AREA.  AT THIS POINT THE DRIVER SHOULD HAVE REFUSED TO UNLOAD DUE TO SEVERAL ISSUES INVOLVING TANK CAPACITY AND TANK MONITORING.  THE DRIVER MADE THE DECISION TO OFF LOAD AND PROCEEDED TO MAKE THE REQUIRED CONNECTIOSN AND BEGAN THE OFF LOAD PROCESS.  WHILE IN THE OFF LOADING PROCESS THE CUSTOMER TANK OVERFLOWED APPROXIMATELY 20 TO 30 GALLONS.  AT THIS POINT THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE CUSTOMER VALVE AND IN THE PROCESS OF CLOSING THE CUSTOMERS VALVE THE HANDLE CAME OFF IN THE DRIVERS HAND.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO PUT THE HANDLE BACK IN PLACE AND FINISHED CLOSING THE CUSTOMERS VALVE.  PLANT PERSONNEL TOOK CARE OF THE CLEANING UP THE PRODUCT SPILL.  THE CUSTOMER WAS ABLE TO SUPPLY A DRUM TO PUT THE PRODUCT IN AND OFFERED ASSISTANCE OF ONE OF THEIR EMPLOYEES TO ASSIST THE DRIVER IN WALKING THE PRODUCT HOSE CLEAR.  THE DRIVER RELIEVED THE PRESSURE IN THE OFF LOADING HOSE THROUGH A BLEEDER LINE PRIOR TO DISCONNECTING THE OFF LOADING HOSE.  WHEN THE DRIVER STARTED TO DISCONNECT THE PRODUCT HOSE, PRODUCT STARTED TO SPRAY FROM AROUND THE CONNECTION.  THE DRIVER WAS EXPOSED TO THE PRODUCT AND RECEIVED 1ST DEGREE BURN TO THE UPPER PART OF HIS LEG ABOVE HIS KNEE AND THE TOP OF HIS FOOT.  THE DRIVER USED A WATER HOSE THAT WAS IN THE AREA WHERE THE UNLOADING TOOK PLACE.  EMS WAS NOTIFIED AND DISPATCHED TO THE PLANT FACILITY AND THE DRIVER WAS TREATED AT THE PLANT FACILITY AND WAS NOT TRANSPORTED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER FAILED TO EXECUTE PROPER PROCEDURES FOR DELIVERING AND OFF LOADING THE CUSTOMER'S PRODUCT.  CTL POLICY IS TO OBTAIN PROPER VERIFICIATION OF TANK CAPACITY, UNLOADING INSTRUCTIONS AND TANK MONITORING.  THE DRIVER WAS ALSO FAILED TO FOLLOW CTL POLICY IN REGARDS TO PROPER USE OF PERSONAL PROTECTION EQUIPMENT.  THE DRIVER WAS SUSPENDED FROM DUTY UNTIL A COMPLETE EVALUATION COULD BE MADE.  THE DRIVER WAS EVALUATED FOR 1 WEEK ON ALL ASPECTS OF LOADING AND UNLOADING, COMPANY POLICY AND PROPER VERIFICATION PROCESS WHILE MAKING DELIVERIES.

TWO WHEELCHAIR BATTERIES WERE PLACED IN AN APPROVED CARDBOARD BOX FOR TRANSPORT ON AIRCRAFT IN NEWARK, NJ.  THE DESTINATION WAS ALBUQUERQUE, NM WITH A STOP IN DALLAS/FORT WORTH, TX.  ON ARRIVAL IN ALBUQUERQUE ONE OF THE BOXES SHOWED SIGNS OF LEAKAGE AND BATTERY ACID WAS FOUND POOLED IN THE BOTTOM DOOR SEAL OF THE CARGO COMPARTMENT.  THE ACID WAS RINSED FOR 2 MINUTES WITH WATER AND AREA WAS WIPED DRY.  AN EMPLOYEE ENTERED THE CARGO COMPARTMENT AND CAME IN CONTACT WITH RESIDUE FROM THE CLEANUP.  EMPLOYEE SUSTAINED BURNS ON RIGHT LEG AND WAS TREATED AND RELEASED FROM LOCAL CLINIC.  THE AREA IN THE CARGO COMPARTMENT WAS RE-EVALUATED AND RE-CLEANED.  THE BATTERY BOX WITH SPILLED ACID WAS FOUND TO BE MISSING THE INNER PLASTIC BAG.

THIS RAIL CAR WAS OBSERVED LEAKING DURING A YARD INSPECTION BY LDEQ.  UPON CLOSER INSPECTION THE LIQUID VALVE WAS FOUND TO BE PARTIALLY OPEN AND THE PLUG WAS LOOSE.  VALVE WAS CLOSED AND PLUG WAS MADE TOOL TIGHT.

column168: First, this report is submitted late due to our inability to obtain adequate information on the load from the appropriate parties.  Additionally, once final damage costs are known, a follow-up report will be submitted. Driver directed to p/u intermodal container at pier 64 in Port Elizabeth. Container is a 20 ft. box containing 14x1375 Kg IBC's. Driver was transporting from pier to local freight forwarder about a mile away for transloading.  While rounding a curve at a very slow speed (estimated to be below 5 mph as attested by a witness) the vehicle rolled onto its left side. When this occurred, one of the IBC's ruptured causing discharge of the material. The police from the Port Authority of New York & New Jersey (which controls this area)arrived on scene and took charge. We are not sure if the consignee (via the freight forwarder) or the Port Authority Police directed a clean-up crew to the scene for mitigation of the spill. Representatives from HMHTTC and the Union County Haz-Mat team responded and cleaned the spill, righted the vehicle and re-opened the roadway. NO INDIVIDUALS SUSTAINED INJURIES AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE, however, the vehicle driver was transported to a local hospital for examination of bruises and sore muscles resulting from the accident. The driver was examined and released and is fine.
column169: In this writer's opinion, this mishap resulted from several miscalculations and over-loading of this container. First, the original pick-up order called for the pick-up of a quantity of 8 x 20' sea containers each containing 14 IBC's @ 1375 Kg net.  The original shipping order provided a gross weight of the containers in pounds while there was no such unit of measurement provided for the individual containers. It was later discovered that these could only have been measured in kilograms which, had  they been so noted, would have clearly shown that these containers were loaded either over their designed gross weight, or double stacked in such a way that a rollover would be all but inevitable at some point. The vehicle driver in this instance is usually extremely cautious and understands the potentialities of a top-heavy load. As a matter of fact, he was going so slowly that vehicles following him were blowing their horns in an attempt to get him to move along. Additionally, there would appear to be some question about how the load was blocked and braced although it cannot be determined fully at this point in time.

column168: AT 0415 CDT, YAZOO SUB CN RTC IN HOMEWOOD, IL NOTED NORTH SWITCH AT ANDING MS, SHOWING OUT OF CORRESPONDENCE.  CN TRAINS M33491-08 AND G86971-09 WERE LINED UP FOR A MEET AT ANDING, MS WITH M33491-08 TAKING THE SIDING.  AFTER NOTING THE SWITCH OUT OF CORRESPONDENCE, RTC TRIED TO CONTACT BOTH TRAINS WITHOUT SUCCESS.  SHORTLY THEREAFTER CN POLICE ADVISED THAT THEY HAD RECEIVED A CALL ADVISING OF A DERAILMENT AND FIRE JUST NORTH OF THE ANDING, MS SIDING.  FOUR LOCOMOTIVES AND EIGHT CARS ON TRAIN G86971-09 AS WELL AS TWO LOCOMOTIVES AND NINE CARS ON M33491 HAD DERAILED.  SEVEN RESIDUE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CAR WERE INVOLVED.  DIESEL FUEL FROM THE SIX LOCOMOTIVES CAUGHT FIRE AND TWO OF THE LPG RESIDUE CARS WERE IN THE POOL FIRE.  DURING THE FIRE EACH OF THE CARS OVER PRESSURED FROM THE HEAT OF THE FIRE CAUSING THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVES TO OPERATE NORMALLY AND RELEASE PRESSURE AS WELL AS LPG VAPOR TO THE ATMOSPHERE.

GULF DRIVER WENT TO THE RIGHT TO MISS THE VEHICLE.  TRAILER TIRES WENT ON SOFT SHOULDER ANDTURNED TRUCK OVER.  TRUCK AND TRAILER LANDED ON ITS SIDE HOLE.  FRONT #1 COMP & 2# COMP. column168: 07/28/05: 0945 AM, MORRISVILLE (PA) YARD, YPMO-01 SWITCHING IN YARD AND NOTED PRODUCT RELEASE FROM TOP OF TANK CAR PROX 47742, LOAD PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, NOS (CLASS 3, PG III).  YARD NOTIFIED CUSTOMER, AND 24-HOUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PHONE NUMBER ON WAYBILL (IMPERIAL OIL CHEMICAL DIVISION, SARNIA, ON, CANADA, 1-519-339-2145) AND CR S.T.O. CR S.T.O. ALSO NOTIFIED CR'S RISK MANAGEMENT DEPT.'S N. FERRONE AND A. RICHTER.  EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR REACT ALSO NOTIFIED AND REQUESTED AT SCENE.  INITIAL INFORMATION WAS THAT THE CAR WAS LEAKING FROM MANWAY COVER AREA (CAR ONLY EQUIPPED WITH A PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE AT THE "B" END TOP 1/3 OF THE CAR, AND A MANWAY.  A PERMANENTLY CLOSURE FLANGED-FITTING WAS AT THE OPPOSITE "A" END OF THE CAR, PERHAPS A FORMER PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE LOCATION.)  INSPECTION BY CR'S RICHTER AND REACT NOTED THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE NOT AS SECURED AS THEY COULD BE.  OPENING THE MANWAY COVER, NOTED PRODUCT LEVEL AT 6" LINE ON THE OUTAGE GAUGE (PRODUCT LEVEL AT THAT MEASUREMENT FROM TOP OF INNER SHELL.)  THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS ALSO NOTED TO BE DISFIGURED AND STRETCHED ON THE HINGED SIDE OF THE MANWAY COVER.  GASKET WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH VITON MANWAY NOZZLE GASKET AND MANWAY COVER SECURED.  AT CR'S REQUEST, THE CAR WAS MOVED PRIOR TO BEING DELIVERED TO THE ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE.  AFTER MOVING THE CAR 1 1/2 CAR LENGTHS, A QUICK STOP SHOWED NO SIGNS OF LEAKAGE.  HOWEVER, UPON MOVING THE CAR BACK THE SAME LENGTH TO COUPLE ("B" END COUPLING, LOCATION OF PRD), PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE PRD (APPROXIMATELY 1 GALLON).  DUE TO THE WEATHER AND HIGH EVAPORATION RATE OF THE PRODUCT, THE SPILL ON THE CAR QUICKLY DISAPPEARED.  NO PRODUCT NOTED TO HAVE CONTACTED THE GROUND.  CAR WAS MOVED TO THE MORRISVILLE YARD SHOP TRACK.  DECISION MADE TO OFF-LOAD APPROXIMATELY 1-2000 GALLONS DUE TO OVERLOAD.  FURTHER CONFERENCE CALLS WITH SHIPPER, CONSIGNEE, CR AND REACT CONCLUDED THAT THE SHIPPER WOULD MAKE ARRANGEMENTS FOR A CLEAN TANK TRUCK TO RECEIVE A FULL LOAD THE FOLLOWING DAY FRIDAY, 7/29/05.  7/29/05: 0830AM; SHIPPER DISPATCHED TANK TRUCK FROM LANGER TRANSPORT (TANK #3316, DOT-SPECIFICATION 407SS, 7000 GAL. CAPCY.)
column169: TANK CAR OVERLOADED BY SHIPPER.  MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS DEFORMED AND DID NOT PRESURE SEAL FOR THE MANWAY COVER.  A WELDED RING ON TOP OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE APPEARED OFF-CENTER, WHICH DID NOT PERMIT PROPER SEATING OF THE GASKET, NOR THE MANWAY COVER.  BOLTS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT.  ADDITIONALLY, I QUESTION THE LOCATION OF THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) IN RELATION TO THE CENTER OF THE CAR.  THE PRD WAS LOCATED TOWARDS THE "B" END, APPROXIMATELY 1/2 WAY BETWEEN THE CENTER OF THE CAR AND THE END, WHERE IT WOULD BE SUBJECTED TO MORE SURGE DYNAMICS AND HIGH PRESSURE RISES DUE TO NORMAL OPERATIONG IN TRANSIT, AS OPPOSED TO THE CENTER OF THE CAR.  THE TANK CAR WAS ALSO A SPECIFICATION 111A60W1 AND WAS EQUIPPED WITH A 75 PSI MIDLAND INTERNAL PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE.

column168: 7/21/05, 10:25AM: TANK CAR PPGX 2671, LOAD SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLUTION (70%), 8, UN 1824, RQ, ARRIVED ON CR TRAIN SA42 FROM NEWARK (OAK ISLAND), NJ, AT 1150AM 7/20/05.  CREW OF SA2 AND YARDMASTER NOTED PRODUCT RESIDUE ON TANK CAR AS IT WAS BEING PULLED BY THE YARD OFFICE FOR CUSTOMER DELIVERY.  IT APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN LEAKING FROM THE TOP AREA.  CAR SET OUT AND ISOLATED ON TRACK #12.  CR RISK MGMT. A. RICHTER NOTIFIED AND ENROUTE.  E.R. CONTRACTOR REACT ALSO CONTACTED AND ENROUTE.  SHIPPER CONTACTED CR S.T.O. AND CONFERENCED TO RICHTER TO ADVISE PRODUCT WAS 70% CONCENTRATION OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE.  BROWNS YARD TRAINMASTER ALSO CONTACTED CONSIGNEE, HERCULES, PARLIN, NJ FOR ASSISTANCE.  INITIAL INSPECTION BY CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVE NOTED THE SAFETY VENT FRANGIBLE DISC HAD RUPTURED.  CR'S RICHTER AND REACT'S R. GOULD REMOVED THE BLOWN 165# STAINLESS RUPTURE DISC AND DISC'S GASKET.  SAFETY VENT WIPED DOWN, CLEANED OF RESIDUE, AND DISC/GASKET IN-KIND WAS REPLACED AND SECURED.  REACT NEUTRALIZED SPILLED MATERIAL ON TANK CAR WITH HOUSEHOLD VINEGAR AND WATER SOLUTION, CONTAINING NEUTRALIZATION RINSE WATER ON CHEMICAL PADS, WHICH ARE TO BE PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY REACT.  AREAS ON TANK CAR WERE TESTED WITH PH PAPER, AND FOUND ALL EFFECTED AREAS NEUTRALIZED.  AREAS WHERE TANK CAR HAD BEEN REPORTED TO BE LOCATED SINCE ITS ARRIVAL AT BROWNS YARD WERE EXAMINED, AND NO EVIDENCE OF SPILLAGE ON GROUND WAS NOTED.  ADDITIONAL, NO EVIDENCE OF SPILLAGE DIRECT TO GROUND WHERE CAR WAS ISOLATED.  ALL OTHER FITTINGS AND CLOSURES INSPECTED, NOTING ONE OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS (ONE OF TWO SAFETY BOLTS BY THE MANWAY HANDLE) WAS NOTED NOT TOOL TIGHT.  SECURED DURING INSPECTION.  CAR OKAYED FOR DELIVERY TO ORIGINAL CUSTOMER AT 3:00 PM.

column168: 7/17/2005: TANK CAR GATX 30402, LOAD TRIETHYLAMINE, CLASS 3 (8), UN 1296, PG II, RQ, ARRIVED AT CONRAIL'S LIVERNOIS (DETROIT), MI YARD ON CSXT'S Q30417 AT APPROXIMATELY 1640 HOURS, ON #3 RECEIVING.  AN ODOR DETECTED BY THE CREW HAD THEM CONTACT A CSXT POLICE OFFICER WHO WAS IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY OF THE YARD.  HIS FURTHER EXAMINATION FOUND PRODUCT CASCADING DOWN FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  HE CONTACTED CHEMTREC, AND OTHER CONRAIL PERSONNEL.  LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTACTED BY CONRAIL, ALONG WITH OTHER REQUIRED AND/OR NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS.  FURTHER INSPECTION BY CONRAIL'S MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT, AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, SRS, HIRED BY CONSIGNEE, NOTED PRODUCT RELEASE HAD ORIGINATED FROM THE MANWAY COVER.  ONE OF SIX MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE.  WHEN MANWAY COVER WAS OPENED TO VISUALLY INSPECT PRODUCT, IT WAS REPORTED THAT THE LIQUID LEVEL WAS APPROXIMATELY 1-2" FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE MANWAY NOZZLE (LEAKAGE FROM MANWAY HAD STOPPED AS THE TEMPERATURE COOLED, AND PRIOR TO THE PHYSICAL INSPECTION DESCRIBED, INDICATING POSSIBLE OVERLOAD OF PRODUCT BY SHIPPER/PREPARER OF RAIL CAR).  ADDITIONALLY, IT WAS NOTED BY CONRAIL MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT, AND CONSIGNEE E.R. CONTRACTOR THAT THE MANWAY COVER GASKET WAS DETERIORATED.  NEW GASKET MATERIAL WAS SUPPLIED BY E.R. CONTRACTOR, FORMED AND APPLIED TO THE MANWAY COVER.  AT CONRAIL'S REQUEST, APPROXIMATELY 1,000 GALLONS WAS TRANSFERRED FROM THE RAIL CAR INTO A CONSIGNEE-SUPPLIED TANK/VAC TRUCK.  CAR WAS SEALED AND OKAYED FOR TRANSPORTATION TO ORIGINAL CONSIGNEE AT APPROXIMATELY 0500 HOURS, 7/18/05.

column168: A CHLORINE LEAK WAS REPORTED BY BORDEN & REMINGTON TO PIONEER ON JULY 15TH AT 8:13 AM.  THE LEAK WAS DISCOVERED AT THEIR SITE BEFORE STARTING THE UNLOADING OPERATION.  THE RAIL CAR WAS STILL TEMPORARY STORAGE.  THE RAIL CAR CONTAINED 180 000 LBS OF CHLORINE AT THE TIME OF REPORTING.  PIONEER SENT HAZMAT TRAINED PERSONNEL TO HELP BORDEN & REMINGTON PERSONNEL HANDLE THE SITUATION.  IT WAS UNCOVERED THAT THE LEAK WAS COMING UNDERNEATH THE FLANGE OF THE RIGHT VAPOR ANGLE VALVE AS PER CHLORINE MANUFACTURER TERMINOLOGY.  AN EMERGENCY C-KIT WAS APPLIED TO MITIGATE THE LEAK.  IN THE FOLLOWING DAYS, BORDEN & REMINGTON PROCEEDED WITH THE UNLOADING OF THE CHLORINE RAIL CAR.  ONCE THE TRANSFER WAS COMPLETED.  PIONEER SENT, TO THE RAIL CAR LOCATION, A PIONEER REPRESENTATIVE ALONG WITH AN EMERGENCY CONTRACTOR TO DEGAS THE CHLORINE RAIL CAR IN A DILUTED SOLUTION OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE AND PURGE IT WITH NITROGEN.  AS A PRECAUTION, THE VAPOR VALVE WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW ONE.  THIS OPERATION TOOK PLACE ON AUGUST 3RD AND AUGUST 4TH.  NO LEAKAGE WAS EXPERIENCED DURING THE TANK CAR CLEAN UP.  DURING THE CLEAN UP OPERATION, A VISUAL INSPECTION OF THE DOME PLATE AND THE VALVE WAS PERFORMED.  THE GAS VALVE WAS IN EXCELLENT CONDITIONS.  HOWEVER, THE GASKET GROOVES LOCATED ON THE PRSSURE PLATE SHOWED IN 2 SPECIFIC AREAS.  THE THICKNESS OF THE GROOVES WERE LESS IN THESE SPECIFIC AREAS.  IT IS BELIEVE THAT AN IMPACT ON THE GROOVES DURING THE VALVE INSTALLATION OR GASKET REMOVAL COULD BE AT THE SOURCE OF THE PROBLEM.
column169: IN LIGHT OF THE OBSERVATIONS, PIONEER IS PROCEEDING IN PROVIDING REFRESHER TRAINING ON VALVE INSTALLATION, VALVE MAINTENANCE AND GASKET REMOVAL PROCEDURES TO THE CHLORINE OPERATORS INVOLVED IN THESE OPERATIONS.  OUR INTERNAL PROCEDURES DO INCLUDE A MENTION ON THE IMPORTANCE OF USING PROPER TOOLS SUCH AS A BRASS SCREWDRIVER AND NOT A METAL SCREWDRIVER IN ORDER TO PREVENT IMPACT OR GOUGE ON THE GROOVES.

column168: ON 14 JULY 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 10:30 AM, YELLOW TRUCKING COMPANY BACKED UP TO THE LOADING DOCKS OF BLDG 340 RAFB GA. TO UNLOAD A PALLET OF POLYURETHANE THINNER PACKED IN 5 GAL METAL CONTAINERS.  TWO OF THE CANS HAD BEEN DAMAGED AND WERE LEAKING ON THE CARDBOARD MATERIAL ON THE PALLET.  THE FIRE DEPT AND SPILL TEAM AT R.A.F.B. WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE.  THE EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED DUE TO THE VAPORS BEING EMITTED.  THE FIRE CHIEF ORDERED THE TRUCK DRIVER TO PULL AWAY FROM THE BUILDING AND ALLOW THE EMPLOYEES TO RETURN TO THE BUILDING.  THE ELLIS ENVIRONMENTAL GROUP OVER PACKED THE LEAKING ASSETS, REMOVED THE WET CARDBOARD PAPER AND STRETCH WRAP.  THE CANS LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 3 GALS.

column42: RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, EXCEPTED PACKAGE-INSTRUMENTS OR ARTICLES
column168: AT AROUND 1500 ON 7/26/2005 MATERIALS WERE RECEIVED WITHOUT AN INVENTORY FROM CALVERT CLUFFS NUCLEAR POWER PLANT (CCNPP).  UPON RECEIPT A METAL CONTAINER WAS IDENTIFIED AND OPENED FOR INSPECTION.  A DETECTOR WITH A RADIATION SYMBOL STICKER WAS IDENTIFIED.  THE STICKER INFORMATION COULD NOT BE CLEARLY READ AT THE TIME.  THE DETECTOR WAS ENCLOSED BACK INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  THERE WERE A TOTAL OF 3 IDENTICAL CONTAINERS.  AROUND 1700 CCNPP WAS NOTIFIED OF THE DETECTORS WITH RADIATION STICKERS.  ON 7/27/2005 2 CCNPP EMPLOYEES ARRIVED TO EVALUATE THE MATERIAL IN QUESTION.  THEY IDENTIFIED THE RADIATION STICKER AS INFORMATION FOR AN AM-241 SOURCE WITH 100 NANOCURIES EACH.  TOTAL ACTIVITY FOR ALL 3 CONTAINERS IS 300 NANOCURIES.  THE DETECTORS WERE DETERMINED TO BE 3 OBSOLETE MAIN STEAM RADIATION MONITORS THAT USED THE AM-241 SOURCE TO GENERATE A VERY SMALL ELECTRICAL CURRENT.  DETECTORS ALSO WERE PRESSURIZED WITH XENON.  THE DETECTORS WERE NEVER ISNTALLED AND BECAME OBSOLETE EQUIPMENT.  THEY REMAINED IN THE ORIGINAL PACKAGING AT CCNPP UNTIL DISPOSED OF AS SALVAGE MATERIALS.  THESE DETECTORS WOULD HAVE BEEN IDENTIFIED AS UN2911 AND UN2036 MARKINGS AS WELL AS BEING SHIPPED WITH THE DOT EXEMPTION PAPERWORK OF DOT-E9030.  ON 7/28/2005 THE DETECTORS WERE SHIPPED BACK TO CCNPP BY QUALIFIED SHIPPING TECHNICIAN.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION OF THE SHIPMENT REVEALED APPROXIMATELY 1 POUND OF MAGNESIUM PERCHLORATE IN A PLASTIC CONTAINER.  THIS PACKAGE WOULD BE MARKED WITH UN1475 AS WELL AS AN OXIDIZER LABEL (DIVISION 5.1).  THE MATERIAL WAS ALSO SHIPPED BACK TO CCNPP BY A QUALIFIED SHIPPING TECHNICIAN.
column169: SHIPPER SHOULD BE COGNIZANT OF ANY HAZARDOUS MATERIALS PRESENTED FOR SHIPMENT AND PROVIDE PROPER IDENTIFICATION MARKINGS.  SHIPPER WAS UNAWARE THAT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS HAD BEEN INCLUDED AS PART OF THE SHIPMENT.  A FULL INVENTORY OF MATERIALS SHOULD BE PROVIDED WITH SHIPMENT AND WOULD HAVE PREVENTED INADVERTANT SHIPMENT OF AN UNDECLARED MATERIAL.  A PROMPT INVESTIGATION WAS CONDUCTED TO EVALUATE THE ISSUE AND RESULTS WERE COMMUNICATED TO BOTH THE RESPONSIBILE GROUP AND SITE PERSONNEL.  ALL COMPENSATORY CORRECTIVE ACTIONS HAD BEEN COMPLETED AND LONG TERM CORRECTIVE ACTIONS WILL BE IMPLEMENTED, AS APPROPRIATE, TO ENSURE A SIMILAR ISSUE DOES NOT OCCUR.

column168: DURING SWITCHING MOVEMENT IN RAILYARD, THE DRAFT ASSEMBLY SLACK RAN-IN WHEN COUPLING RAILCARS AND PRODUCT SPLASHED OUT OF GATX 20915.  THE PRODUCT SPRAY CONTACTED THE BNSF REMOTE CONTROL OPERATOR WHOM WAS STANDING ON THE GROUND NEAR THE COUPLING RAILCARS.  THIS EMPLOYEE SUSTAINED CHEMICAL CONTACT ON HIS LEFT ARM, NECK AND FACE.  THIS EMPLOYEE WAS IMMEDIATELY TAKEN TO THE YARD OFFICE AND THE IMPACTED AREA OF HIS BODY WAS WATER WASHED.  AFTERWARDS, EMPLOYEE WENT TO A LOCAL HOSPITAL WHERE HE WAS EXAMINED, TREATED FOR CHEMICAL BURNS AND RELEASED.  SUBSEQUENTLY, THIS EMPLOYEE HAS NOT YET RETURNED TO WORK.  INITIAL INSPECTION OF GATX 20915 REVEALED THE FILL HOLE GASKET WAS MISALIGNED.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE WITH GATX MOBILE REPAIR UNIT TO REPLACE THIS GASKET ON 8/04/05.  FILL HOLE GASKET WAS REPLACED ON 8/04 AND CONFIRMED BY REPAIR CREW THAT IT WAS NOT SEATED PROPERLY.  ALSO, SOME CORROSION PITTING WAS PRESENT ON THE METAL AROUND THE GASKET SEATING AREA.  SPILLAGE AROUND THE TOP AREA OF TANK CAR DRIED.  A SIMILAR SHIPMENT (SHIPPER ORIGIN AND COMMODITY) THAT WAS ADJACENT TO THE GATX 20915 WAS NOTED WITH THE MANWAY NOZZLE GASKET PARTIALLY HANGING OVER THE NOZZLE LIP.  THIS TANK CAR WAS NOT LEAKING PRODUCT AND IT WAS ISOLATED IN THE RAILYARD FOR FUTURE PRODUCT TRANSFER AND FORWARDING TO A QUALIFIED REPAIR SHOP AFTERWARDS.  OTHER SIMILAR SHIPMENTS THAT WERE STILL ON THE BNSF SYSTEM WERE SURVEYED, CAPTURED AND INSPECTED BY THE BNSF MECHANICAL TEAM.  THESE INSPECTIONS RESULTED IN NO DEFECTS OR SECUREMENT DEFICIENCY DISCOVERIES.

Driver called and informed customer of drum damage and potential for shortage.  Consignee agreed to accept drum and inspect for quantity. column168: AN OVER 70 REWRAP PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE DMP CAGE FOR REPACKAGING.  THE OUTER BOX WAS FAILING.  THERE WERE NO HAZ MAT MARKINGS ON THE OUTER PKG.  AS THE REWRAPPER WAS PUTTING THE CONTENTS IN A NEW BOX, I NOTICED THE DIAMOND CLASS 9 LABELS AND "UN3268/AIR BAG MODULES" ON THE TWO INNER BOXES.  THIS OCCURRED AT 07:15 ON 7/25/05.  RMP ARON OLSON CALLED THE HAZ MAT HOTLINE TO VERIFY THAT THESE PKGS DO REQUIRE SHIPPER PAPERS.  ON 7/26, HE CALLED THE CONSIGNEE (CHRISTIAN TERMORE) WHO WILL PICK UP THE PACKAGE AT CUSTOMER COUNTER TODAY.  THE AIR BAG MODULES ARE NOT DAMAGED OR LEAKING.  THE OTHER AUTO PARTS ARE OK TOO.

column42: CARBON DIOXIDE, SOLID OR DRY ICE
column168: PACKAGE WAS IN AIRDOCK WHEN IT WAS DISCOVERED.  SOMEONE FROM THE AIRDOCK NOTICED THAT THE BOX WAS COLD TO THE TOUCH.  A SUPERVISOR WAS NOTIFIED AND OPENED BOX AFTER PERMISSION FROM HMSC.  PACKAGE HAD ASSORTED POT PIES WITH FREE DRY ICE.  SECOND CALL TO HMSC AND INSTRUCTED TO FILL OUT HM10 AND 5800.1 FORMS AND TO THEN PUT PACKAGE ON HOLD.  PICTURES WERE TAKEN AND NO REJECTION CHECK LIST WAS FILLED OUT AS INSTRUCTED BY LEAN FROM HMSC.
column169: THE SHIPPER NEEDS TO DECLARE THE PACKAGE AS HAZARDOUS ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX.  TO SHIP DRY ICE YOU NEED THE NAME OF THE PRODUCT BEING REFRIGERATED, THE WEIGHT OD DRY ICE, AND DRY ICE OR CARBON DIOXIDE, SOLID NEEDS TO BE STATED ON THE OUTSIDE OF PACKAGE.  AS LONG AS THE WEIGHT OF DRY ICE DOES NOT EXCEED 5.07 LB OR 2.3 KG, THIS IS ALL YOU NEED ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE BOX.  IF THE WEIGHT OF DRY ICE EXCEEDS THSI AMOUNT SHIPPING PAPERS ARE REQUIRED.  AN HM10 WAS ALSO FILLED OUT, SO THE SHIPPER WILL BE NOTIFIED OF THEIR MISTAKE AND HAS THE KNOWLEDGE NOW ON HOW TO PROPERLY PACK DRY ICE.

column168: Trailer doors were opened in preparation for the trailer to be backed to the dock. All contents of the package leaked out. The package was eventually placed into a salvage container and disposed of properly.

column168: WHILE IN THE LOADING PROCESS, DRIVER FAILED TO SHUT OFF LOADING PUMP WHICH RESULTED IN AN OVERFLOW OF MATERIAL ONTO THE GROUND AT THE SHIPPER'S SITE.  APPROXIMATELY 58 GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS RELEASED.  PERSONNEL AT THE SHIPPER'S SITE AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY, OP-TECH IN TONAWANDA, NY, JOINED EFFORTS IN THE CLEANUP PROCESS.  TWO ROLL-OFF BOXES OF NON-HAZARDOUS CONTAMINATED GRAVEL, PAVEMENT, AND DIRT WERE COLLECTED FOR DISPOSAL AT A FUTURE DATE.  NO MATERIAL ENTERED ANY WATERWAYS OR DRAINS.
column169: RE-TRAINING ON TANKER PROCEDURES AND SAFETY WAS IMPLEMENTED IMMEDIATELY.  THREE SESSIONS, THREE TIMES A WEEK ARE BEING HELD IN THE CARRIER'S TERMINAL.  TRAINING WILL THEN GO ON THE ROAD TO FINISH WITH ANY DRIVERS WHO DIDN'T ATTEND THE SESSIONS IN THE TERMINAL.  ALL DISPATCHERS, MECHANICS, LOAD PLANNERS, CUSTOMER SERVICE AND SAFETY/COMPLIANCE PERSONNEL WERE ALSO REQUIRED TO ATTEND THE TRAINING.

column168: - A 20FT BOX CONTAINER LOADED WITH 77 EACH 55 GALLON DRUMS OF CLASS 3 MATERIAL DEPARTED THEODORE, AL. FOR NEW ORLEANS, LA.  - THE DRUMS WERE LOADED ON THE FLOOR OF THE CONTAINER AND STACKED 2 HIGH WITH CARDBOARD SHEETING BETWEEN LAYERS.  - THE LOAD WAS SECURED WITH 2" NYLON STRAPS (TOP & BOTTOM) AT THE REAR OF THE CONTAINER TO PREVENT SHIFTING THROUGH DOORS.  - FAILURE OF PACKAGE APPEARS TO HAVE RESULTED FROM PACKAGES BOUNCING VERTICALLY AND DAMAGING BOTTOM CHIME OF NEIGHBORING PACKAGE.  - FRICTION OF MORE VERTICAL BOUNCING CAUSED THE FAILURE OF THE PACKAGE.
column169: -FUTURE SHIPMENTS WILL BE MORE CLOSELY INSPECTED TO DETERMINE WEAKNESSES DUE TO AGE OF PACKAGE, POSSIBLE DAMAGE AT SEAMS, AND GENERAL APPERANCE LEADING TO QUESTIONABLE INTEGRITY.  - LOADING PROCEDURES WILL BE REVIEWED FOR POTENTIAL IMPROVEMENTS.  - OPERATORS WILL BE PRESENTED DETAILS OF INCIDENT DURING NEXT SAFETY MEETING TO EVALUATE POSSIBLE IMPROVEMENTS TO PROCESS.

column168: ON FRIDAY, JULY 29TH TANK CAR GATX 7292 (LOAD - SULFURIC ACID) WAS REPORTED WITH WETNESS ON SIDES OF CAR BY A MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT EMPLOYEE AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S FLORENCE, SOUTH CAROLINA.  THE RAILCAR WAS ISOLATED AS PER OUR EMERGENCY RESPONSE PLAN.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT AND REPAIR THE CONTAINER.  THE SHIPPER, US WASTE INDUSTRIES, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  ONCE ON SITE, THE CONTRACTOR DETERMINED THAT THE NON-RECLOSING PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE 165 POUND FRANGIBLE DISC HAD FAILED.  THE CONTRACTOR DID NOT HAVE A REPLACEMENT DISC IN STOCK.  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED TO OBTAIN A REPLACEMENT DISK, HOWEVER THEY ALSO DID NOT HAVE THE CORRECT DISC READILY AVAILABLE.  THE CONTRACTOR WASHED DOWN THE SIDES OF THE CAR AND NEUTRALIZED THE SMALL AREA UNDER THE CAR WHERE ACID HAD DRIPPED ONTO THE BALLAST MEDIA.  ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO OVERNIGHT A REPLACEMENT DISC TO THE CONTRACTOR.  THE FRANGIBLE DISC WAS REPLACED ON SATURDAY, JULY 30TH AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION.

column168: ON 07/29/05 AT 1500 HR, TRAIN R67629 WAS TRAVELING SOUTH THROUGH FOSTERVILLE, TN., AT MILE POST 000J45 WHEN THE 50TH HEAD CAR, CGLX 460, LOAD OF SODIUM CHLORATE, EXPERIENCED A ROLLER BEARING FAILURE, CAUSING THE WHEEL TO COME IN CONTACT WITH THE ALUMINUM HOPPER CHUTE.  FRICTION FROM THE WHEEL COMING IN CONTACT WITH THE ALUMINUM HOPPER CHUTE, RUBBED A 16 INCH BY 2 HOLE IN THE CHUTE.  AS THE TRAIN WAS TRAVELING WITH THE ROLLER BEARING FAILURE, THE WHEEL HIT A SWITCH, BROKE THE RAIL AND SHEARED OFF BOTTOM UNLOADING TUBE CAP.  THE TRAIN CAME TO A SAFE STOP PREVENTING FURTHER DAMAGE TO THE RAIL CAR.  APPROXIMATELY 22 POUNDS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED FROM THE CAR.  THE DEFECTIVE WHEEL WAS REPLACED.  THE HOLE IN THE CHUTE WAS PATCHED WITH SHEETS OF ALUMINUM AND GASKET MATERIAL.  THE UNLOADING TUBE CAP WAS COVERED WITH SHEETS OF ALUMINUM AND GASKET MATERIAL TO PREVENT ANY MORE PRODUCT FROM LEAKING.  RAIL CAR CONTINUED TO DESTINATION.

THE RETAINER HANDLE WAS THEN SECURED WITH WIRE CABLE, WHEN THE VALVE WAS PLACED INTO THE FULLY CLOSED POSITION.

column168: WHILE UNLOADING FREIGHT AT HARLEY DAVIDSON PAINT IN TOMAHAWK, WI THE HARLEY FORKLIFT DRIVER PUNCTURED TWO 5-GALLON PAIL OF PAINT WITH THE FORKLIFT BLADES.  THIS CAUSED 10 GALLONS OF PAINT TO SPILL OUT.  HARLEY IMMEDIATELY CALLED IN THEIR IN-HOUSE SPILL PREVENTION TEAM TO CONTROL AND CLEAN UP THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPILL, THEY CLEANED UP THE SPILL ALONG WITH CLEANING CON-WAYS TRAILER AND LET THE TRAILER AIR OUT.  HARLEY DISPOSED OF SPILLED PRODUCT.
column169: HARLEY DAVIDSON WILL HANDLE WITH THEIR PERSONNEL TO ELIMINATE THESE SORT OF ACTIONS FROM RECURRING.

Trailer loaded from our Seattle,WA terminal to our Oswego, IL terminal. The trailer was taken by highway to the rail in Seattle and moved by rail to Chicago, IL where our Oswego, IL terminal dispatched a driver to pick it up and move it by highway to Oswego. It was pouring rain the night of the pick up at the rail, nothing was noticed leaking at the time of pick up from the rail. The trailer was taken to our yard where the next day after the rain had quit, the trailer was noticed to be leaking and had an acid smell. The doors were opened and the entire load had shifted. A clean up team was called, they performed the clean up and decon of the trailer. The freight shifted sometime during the load, it is unknow to ABF if the load shifted due to a lack of blocking and bracing in the trailer or if the rail yard dropped the trailer when unloading it off of the rail trailer which would certainly cause the entire load to shift.
column169: The blocking and bracing appeared to be adequate and even well documented before taking the trailer to the rail. All indications are that the rail dropped the trailer but ABF was not present and cannot prove this fact.

column168: On 7/21/05 at 2100 hours, switchmen in yard reported smelling a strong odor coming from ISO containers on a car in the Cotton Warehouse Yard.  Upon inspection of ISO tanks, United States Environmental Services found about 10 ounces of Hexchlorocyclopentadiene leaking around the valve inside the splash box.  The changed the gasket on the valve and stopped the leak.  They said it was defective and was a non-conforming package and could not be shipped until the valve was changed.  The carrier sent their own company, Gulf States Environmental Services to change the valve and charge it with nitrogen.  They changed the valve, charged the car and released it to be moved.

Fuel truck made a left turn to enter I-10 off of I-95 at approx. 10 mph.  The entrance to I-10 is slightly outsloped at that speed the trailer laid on its right side. During role over trailer abraded a 4" x 1/8" crack in the tank wall letting the Jet Fuel leak onto the pavement and down embankment.  From the time of the incidient and the arrival of the Highway Patrol, the Driver obatined the spill kit from the company truck and used it to divert the fuel to the edge of the road.  Within approximately 10 minutes after the incident occured the Arizona Highway Patrol arrived.  Within 20 minutes of the incident the Quartzsite Fire Department arrived, they applied foam to the interior and exterior of the truck and trailer.  For the next four or five hours the Fire Department foamed the truck and trailer until the Hazmat team arrived.  Once the Hazmat team arrived (Environmental Response Inc) the Fire Department and Highway Patrol stood by.  Environmental Response Inc. was contracted to clean spillage. ERI contacted MP Environmental to pump off the jet fuel before righting the trailer. The site was clear by midnight.

ONCE THIS OCCURRED ON THE REVERSE CAMBER TURN THE TANKER PROCEEDED TO ROLL OVER AND CAME TO A REST AGAINST THE GUARD RAILS.  THE IMPACT AGAINST THE GUARD RAIL POST RIPPED AN OPENING IN THE TANK ALLOWING A SLOW BUT STEADY RELEASE OF PRODUCT TO OCCUR.  CLEAN UP BEGAN IMMEDIATELY AND NO FUEL REACHED THE CREEK BELOW THE OVERPASS.  CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS REMOVED AND DISPOSED OF.  GROUNDWATER MONITORING WELLS WERE INSTALLED TO DETECT ANY LEAKING OF ANY RESIDUAL CONTAMINATION.  SEMI-ANNUAL MONITORING INDICATES LEVELS ARE BDL AND CLOSURE IS PENDING.

column168: Discussion with rail yard representative indicate that the MMA tank car was being moved along with other cars in the yard.  The MMA tank car was push/placed on a track and the locomotive then moved onto the adjacent track to push or retrieve other cars.  As the locomotive began to travel back down the track the MMA began to roll toward the switch gear (two tracks narrow back together).  The rail cars that were attached to the locomotive then struck the MMA tank car and pushed it off the track and over onto its side.  The locomotive engineer who sits on the right side of the locomotive was not able to see the MMA tank car rolling, which was on the left side of the locomotive, and was not aware of the impending collision.

column168: Loaded cargo tank had been delivered to consignee.  Operator used yard spotter to pick up cargo tank to move into position to be unloaded at tank farm.  Upon driving approximately 100 yards, unit maneuvered around corner when the kingpin disengaged from the fifth wheel while moving at approximately 5 mph.  Upper coupler slid off fifth wheel, support legs contacted roadway surface (private property), buckled, and bent under.  Support leg bolsters and upper coupler took the brunt of the impact.  Bolsters caused the third ring of the cargo tank to buckle, thus structural damage.  Unloading line of compartment 1 also bent out of position, warranting inspection.    There was no loss of lading from any compartment.  All material was unloaded from the cargo tanks from the domes.  Upon removal of lading, a wrecker was employed to lift the cargo tank, allowing for inspection of the kingpin.  When deemed sound, the cargo tank was attached to a tractor unit.    Cargo tank to be inspected for safety in transport, prior to being returned to the manufacturer for repairs and recertification.
column169: The yard tractor was inspected and found to be operating properly.  It appears that this accident was the result of the operator having made contact with the kingpin release mechanism during movement.  The design of the yard tractor was flawed.  The release mechanism is activated by being pushed in, and is well within reach of an operator's elbow while holding the steering wheel.  A protective box has since been installed to isolate the box from unintentional operation.  A recommendation was also made to the manufacturer to install a protected mechanism.

column168: Fuel delivery vehicle had hooked to facility's bulk storage loading head.  An improper valve line up was performed prior to the commencement of offloading fuel. The estimation of fuel spilled is based on the actual gallons registered in the fuel tank as compared to the net temperature compensated gallons as recorded on the shipper's manifest (Bill of Laden).

column168: The Mission Petroleum - Central Complex is a site with multiple tanks and a combination of both above ground and underground piping and multiple valving configurations - Jim Miller was the second of three drivers loading from this site on July 2nd - Miller connected a product hose to his trailer manifold that was left @ the sump from a previous driver - The main header valve inside the sump had malfunctioned and was frozen in the open position - Miller open a alternate in line 4" ball valve and the main tank valve and began loading - After loading Miller closed the 4" ball valve and started to evacuate product hose - When he released the ears on the hose - It blew off and started spilling oil - Miller dump the hose into the sump to contain flow and started to check valving - Driver # 3 ran over to a second 4" in line ball valve - closed it - and the flow stopped.      Post review of the situation by the drivers revealed that the product line for the tank being pulled actually ran parallel and directly underneath another 4" line and was partially buried  - This partially buried line surfaced and then "T" ed into the 4' line @ the sump area where frozen valve was.   This gave the illusion the #1 ball valve was tied into the man line and controlled the flow.     Additional Notes:  Mission's Production Operator was on location and stated they were aware of the valve problem - Took control of the cleanup and made a temporary repair of the valve and schedule a valve replacement on Tuesday.
column169: Have Mission replace bad sump valve - Pursue load line revamping with individual lines per well name - Mark all lines with highly visible paint with designated color per well - Trial use of locking coupling ears or similar device on load hoses - Develop a reject protocol for unusual and difficult locations.

column168: 0745 HOURS, 07/01/05-CSXT NOTED VAPOR RELEASE FROM DUPX 20194 WHILE CAR WAS AT PARKERSBURG, WV, LOWER YARD.  E. I. DUPONT DE NEMOURS (CONSIGNEE), WASHINGTON (PARKERSBURG), WV RESPONDED.  MR. GALEN COX, (304-863-2790), DUPONT, WASHINGTON, WV ADVISED LEAK WAS FROM THE "DETECTION DEVICE" (VALVE) OF THE "COMBINATION PRESSURE RELIEF SYSTEM.  THE "NON-RECLOSING" PORTION WAS DEFECTIVE AND THE "DETECTION DEVICE" WAS NOT CLOSED.  DUPONT HAZMAT TEAM CLOSED THE "DETECTION DEVICE" VALVE AND LEAK STOPPED.

PACKAGE WAS UNDELIVERABLE AS THE RECIPIENT COULD NOT BE FOUND TO ACCEPT THE PACKAGE.  BEFORE WE RETURNED IT BY AIR, A FEDEX EMPLOYEE CARRYING A BOX FELT WHAT SHE DESCRIBED AS A 'SLOSHING' OR LIQUID MOVING IN THE BOX.  I WAS CALLED & AUTHORIZED HER TO OPEN THE BOX.  IT WAS AT THE TIME THAT WE FOUND SEVERAL BOTTLES OF PERFUME.  MANY OF THOS BOXES/BOTTLES HAD THE WORD 'FLAMMABLE' PRINTED ON THEM.  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR EMERGENCY RESPONSE INFORMATION PROVIDED ON OR WITH THE SHIPMENT.  THE FAA WAS NOTIFIED, I SPOKE TO SA CHRISTEN NIELSEN IN SEA.  THE FREIGHT IS BEING HELD PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION.  SUBSEQUENTLY, THE FAA MADE CONTACT WITH FEDEX IN MOSES LAKE, WAS AND REQUESTED THAT PICTURES BE TAKEN OF THE BOX & CONTENTS.  THAT HAS BEEN ACCOMPLISHED AN SENT IN AN EMAIL TO SA NIELSEN.

column42: FIRE EXTINGUISHERS CONTAINING COMPRESSED OR LIQUEFIED GAS
column62: Conveyer or Material Handling Equipment Mishap
column168: FILE-05-227 DOT SHIPPER- BUCKEYE FIRE EQUIPMENT AWB#-SRW 41343539591 ACT  ON 07/23/2005 AT 0319 EST, THE HAZMAT HOTLINE RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE ROANOKE REGIONAL HUB LOCATED AT 3736 TOM ANDREWS ROAD NW, ROANOKE, VA 24019.  ED MATNEY FROM THE ROANOKE REGIONAL HUB REPORTED THAT THEY HAD A CRUSHED FIRE EXTINGUISHER.  THE HOTLINE CONTACTED HMHTTC SPILL RESPONSE TEAM.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A SKID OF FIRE EXTINGUISHERS INSIDE A TRAILER.  DUE TO LOOSE SHRINK WRAP, A PACKAGE HAD FALLEN OFF OF THE SKID AND HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY A PIECE OF EQUIPMENT AND DISCHARGED.  5.98 KG OF THE PRODUCT WAS LOST.  THE PACKAGE ARRIVED INTO THE ROANOKE REGIONAL HUB VIA TRUCK # 4403.  THIS PACKAGE DID HAVE MARKINGS/LABELS AND A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO AND ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0834 EST.

AS RAMP SERVICE PERSONNEL WERE LOADING THE AFT BULK AREA OF AIRCRAFT N369 FLIGHT 283 FROM MIA TO LAX THEY NOTICED AN ODOR COMING FROM AN UNKNOWN SOURCE.  A/C MUTE MECHANIC TOM CONTESSA RESPONDED AND LOCATED SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  THERE WAS A SPILL OF AN UNDECLARED DG.  THE LOCAL HAZMAT TEAM OPENED THE TNT SHIPPING BAG AND DISCOVERED 1 QUART SIZE CAN OF A PRODUCT CALLED "KEYMX" HAD SPILLED.  THIS MATERIAL IS AN UNSATURATED POLYESTER RESIN AND A CLASS 3 FLAMMABLE LIQUID.  THREE RAMP SERVICE EMPLOYEES WERE PROVIDED MEDICAL TREATMENT FOR INHALATION AND SKIN CONTACT.  THE A/C MUTE MECHANIC ALSO SUSTAINED INHALATION INJURY.
column169: THE SHIPPER TNT USA INC HAS BEEN NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT.  THE SHIPMENT WAS TENDERED TO AMERICAN AIRLINES AND NOT DECLARED AS A DG.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: THIS UNMARKED AND UNDECLARED FIBERBOARD BOX WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING DURING THE PACKAGE SORTING OPERATION.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THERE WERE 4 EXIDE 60 BATTERIES INSIDE A PLASTIC CASE, THERE WAS INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX.  THE BATTERY HAD LEAKED IN THE INBOUND CONTAINER THAT HAD BEEN TRUCKED TO THIS FACILITY.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR THE BOS/FAA TO INVESTIGATE.  STEVEN REDEKER OF THE BOS/FAA WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.  SHIPMENT IS BEING HELD PENDING VISIT.

AT APPROXIMATELY 0900 ON JULY 13TH, JOHN BOICH WAS ADVISED THAT UA945 FRA ORD HAD A SHIPMENT OF UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS ABOARD.  THIS HAZMAT PIECE, UN1072, OXYGEN COMPRESSED, HAD BEEN CROSS LABELED BY CENTRAL GLOBAL CARGO GMBH OF FRANKFURT GERMANY AND WAS MISTAKENLY SENT TO CHICAGO GMBH BY THEIR SHIPPER, RODER PRAZISION GMBH, WITH A FINAL DESTINATION OF WICHITA.  BOICH ADVISED UNITED'S STATION OPERATION CENTER AT O'HARE.  THE SYSTEM OPERATIONS CENTER & CARGO SAFETY DEPARTMENTS AT ITS HEADQUARTERS.  AND THE FAA'S SPECIAL AGENT, ORDE DUPLESSIS.  UNITED'S FRANKFURT FREIGHT FACILITY WAS ALSO NOTIFIED VIA EMAIL.  THE CARGO ARRIVED WITHOUT INCIDENT AT APPROXIMATELY 1015 ON THE 13TH AND WAS TERMINATED HERE AT O'HARE.  SPECIAL AGENT DUPLESSIS CONDUCTED A PHYSICAL INSPECTION OF THE CARGO AND PACKAGING ALONG WITH ALL DOCUMENTATION AT UNITED'S FREIGHT FACILITY.

PRELOAD FIRST RESPONDER, JOHN SINGLETON, WAS NOTIFIED OF WET PACKAGE ON THE CLIFTON TALBE, THERE WAS NO LEAKAGE ON UPS EQUIPMENT.  HE FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND PROCEEDED TO THE "CORROSIVE" RESPONSE SHEET FOR CONTAINMENT AND CLEANUP OF SPILL SINCE THE "CORROSIVE" DIAMOND LABEL WAS VISABLE ON PACKAGE.  HE RECOGNIZED THE PACKAGE AS HAZARDOUS DUE TO A FEW VISABLE INDICATORS: 1) UPS 5-PART LAZER PRINTED SHIPPING PAPERS; 2) "CORROSIVE" DIAMOND LABEL; 3) UN IDENTIFICATION CODE.  HE THEN TRANSPORTED THE WET HAZARDOUS PACKAGE BACK TO THE PROCESSING CENTER FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.  HE THEN PROCEEDED TO PROCESS PACKAGE USING THE "WASTE DISPOSAL FOR FULL DMP FACILITY" CHART.

column168: SYGMA GROUP BROUGHT THE PACKAGE TO THE CENTER AND PUT ON THE AIR TABLE.  CHUCK LOADED IT AND TOOK IT TO THE AIRPORT.  AT THE AIRPORT THEY WERE UNLOADING IT.  BRIAN NOEL FROM URBANA CENTER SHOOK THE PACKAGE, AND SAID IT SOUNDED LIKE AEROSOL CANS.  AT THIS POINT THEY TOOK THE WHITE PAPER OFF THE PACKATE AND SAW THE ORM-D LABEL.  THEY BORUGHT THE PACKAGE BACK TO THE CENTER AND TOLD ANGELA POWELL ABOUT IT AND SHE PUT IN AN EXCEPTION ON IT.  THE PACKAGE WAS NOT DAMAGED.  THE DRIVERS WERE SUSPICIOUS OF IT, AND THAT IS HOW WE FOUND IT.  DANNY CALTON TOLD KEN SACKETT ON THURSDAY AND HE REMEMBERED SYGMA TRYING A SHIP A PACKAGE JUST LIKE THIS ONE EXCEPT WITH OUT THE WHITE PAPER ON IT.  HE TOLD THEM THEY COULD NOT SHIP IT IN THE AIR SYSTEM WITH OUT AN ORM-D AIR STICKER AND SHIPPING PAPERS ON IT.  IT LOOKS LIKE THEY DECIDED TO COVER IT UP AND SHIP IT ANYWAY.

FLOOR OF UNIT WAS ABSORBED WITH OIL DRY AND SWEPT UP; THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED; ALL FREIGHT WAS PUT BACK INTO UNIT AND RELEASED TO CSXI FOR FURTHER TRANSPORTATION.  CAUSE OF INCIDENT IS SHIPPER LIABILITY DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING METHOD AND INADEQUATE BLOCKING AND BRACING; SHIPMENT WAS SINGLE STACK FLOOR LOADED WITHOUT BRACING TO PREVENT FREIGHT SHIFTING INTO AND DAMAGING OTHER FREIGHT; THERE WAS NO BLOCKING AND BRACING TO KEEP FREIGHT FROM SHIFTING ACROSS FLOOR, INTO DOORS AND WALLS OF UNIT DURING NORMAL RAIL TRANSPORTATION. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE ONTO DESTINATION.  NO REMEDIATION WAS NEEDED FOR THIS RELEASE AS ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT OF VAPOR WAS RELEASED.

column168: DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, REPORTED CONTAINER NOSU 223069 WAS LEAKING AN INDUSTRIAL SAND AT THE ICTF YARD, LONG BEACH, CA.  MR. COOPER ADVISED THE CONTAINER WAS WET TO THE CUSTOM'S DOCK FOR INSPECTION.  DEVELOPED THE LADING OF TWELVE EACH, ONE TON SUPER SACKS OF SAND HAD TOPPLED AND TORN INSIDE THE CONTAINER, RELEASING APPROXIMATELY 3000 PONDS OF SAND INSIDE THE CONTAINER AND ONTO THE GROUND.  MR. COOPER ADVISED WHILE HE WAS INSPECTING THE LOAD, SIX EACH, FIVE GALLON PAILS OF PAINT WERE ALSO LOCATED INSIDE THE CONTAINER.  MR. COOPER STATED THE CONTAINER WAS ON HELD UNTIL THE RAIL BILLING WAS CORRECTED.  DEVELOPED THE PAINT WAS NOT PROPERLY CLASSIFIED AS HAZARDOUS ON THE SHIPPERS BILL OF LADING, THUS, NOT PROPERLY TRANSMITTED FOR THE RAIL BILLING.  DURING THE CLENA UP OF THE SAND, THE SHIPPER ARRANGED TO HAVE THE 6 FLAMMABLE LIQUID PAILS REMOVED OR SHIPPED BACK TO THE POINT OR ORIGIN.  ONCE THE SAND WAS CLEANED UP, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO THE PORT FOR VESSEL LOADING.
