DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS CONTACTED BY THE EAST YARD RAMP MANAGER ADVISING A LEAKING CONTAINER.  WAYBILL INFORMATION SHOWED THE CONTENTS AT MIXFRT, AND THE RAMP MANAGER WAS ADVISED TO CONTACT THE LOCAL DAMAGE PREVENTION MANAGER.  SATURDAY MORNING, THE RAMP MANAGER CONTACTED MANAGER COOPER ADVISING OF A LEAKING CONTAINER IN RED ROW.  DEVELOPED IT WAS THE SAME CONTAINER FROM THE PREVIOUS DAY.  MANAGER COOPER CONTACTED TRANSLOADING ENVIRONMENTAL TO INSPECT AND CONTAIN THE LEAK.  TRANSLOADING INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND DEVELOPED IT WAS PLACARDED WITH CORROSIVE PLACARDS.  FIELD TESTING NOTED THE LEAKING LIQUID TO BE NEUTRAL PH.  APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD DRIPPED THROUGH THE FLOORING AT THE LANDING GEAR OF THE CHASSIS.  THE FREE LIQUID WAS CONTAINED WITH ABSORBENT.  MONDAY MORNING, RECEIVED AN MSDS FROM ARCHER DANIELS DESCRIBING ONE OF THE CONTENTS TO BE LATIC ACID, A CORROSIVE LIQUID.  THE REMAINING LADING CONSISTED OF TWO ADDITIONAL COMMODITIES, 65 PAILS OF SODIUM LACTATE, AND 36 DRUMS DRUMS OF SOYBEAN LECITHIN, BOTH NON REGULATED.  P&O WAS ADVISED THE RAIL BILLING WOULD REQUIRE A CHANGE OF ADDRESS THE HAZARDOUS COMMODITY, AND ADM WAS ADVISED TO CONTACT TRANSLOADING TO REMOVE AND INSPECT THE LADING TO LOCATE THE ACTUAL LEAKER.  ON WEDNESDAY, TRAHSLOADING REMOVED THE LADING AND LOCATED ONE LEAKING 55 GALLON DRUM CONTAINING THE SOYBEAN LECITHIN.   THE SIDEWALL OF THE DRUM HAD A SMALL DENT WITH A SMALL CREASE, LOCATED BETWEEN THE LOWER ROLLING HOOP AND BOTTOM CHIME.  THE CRACK ALLOWED PRODUCT TO WEEP FROM THE DRUM, LOSING APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT.  THE DRUM WAS PATCHED AND PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK FOR SECUREMENT.  THE FLOORING WAS CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE, AND THE FREIGHT PLACED BACK INTO THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER.  ON FRIDAY, 7/29, THE CUSTOMER SERVICE CENTER RECEIVED A CORRECTED BILL OF LADING.  ONCE THE COMPUTER RECORDS WERE CORRECTED, THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

UPRR S RESPONSE MANAGEMENT COMMUNICATION CENTER NOTIFIED LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY OF A TANK CAR WITH AN OPEN HATCH COVER IN TRACK 306 IN NEFF YARD, KANSAS CITY, MO.  TANK CAR UTLX 48162 RELEASED VAPORS FROM THE UNSECURED HATCH COVER AND TWO EMPLYOEES WERE EXPOSED TO THE VAPOR AND SUSTAINED EYE, EAR, NOSE, AND THROAT IRRITATION AND CONGESTION.  MR. SEKAVEC CONTACTED ROBERT CULP, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, AND REQUESTED THAT THE TANK CAR NOT BE MOVED UNTIL A RESPONDER COULD CHECK THE CAR.  MR. column168: SAVANNAH OVER THE WEEKEND HAD A SHIPMENT (05-1650) WHICH HAD BEEN A CONCERN AND HAS GROWN IN SCOPE.  WE PICKED UP A LOAD (7/28/05) AT A GENERATOR'S FACILITY (WAH CHANG) IN ALBANY, OR FOR OUR CUSTOMER ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL.  OUR DRIVER J.B COMER WAS ACCOMPANIED BY VINCE BROWN FROM THE ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL.  OUR DRIVER J.B COMER WAS ACCOMPANIED BY VINCE BROWN FROM THE ONYX-VANCOUVER OFFICE.  THE ORIGINAL INTENT WAS TO HAVE THIS LOAD MAKE ADDITIONAL STOPS FOR LOADING AND UNLOADING AT ONYX'S FACILITIES IN VANCOUVER, WAS AND HENDERSON, CO WITH A FINAL DELIVERY SCHEDULED AT VONROLL AMERICAN IN EAST LIVERPOOL, OH.  AFTER LOADING IN ALBANY, ONYX DECIDED WE DIDN'T NEED TO STOP IN VANCOUVER SO THE DRIVER WAS DIRECTED TO PROCEED TO HENDERSON, FOR A MONDAY MORNING APPOINTMENT.  ON SATURDAY OUR DRIVER STOPPED IN CHEYENNE AND BECAME AWARE OF A VERY STRONG ODOR COMING FROM THE TRAILER, UPON FURTHER INVESTIGATION, HE NOTED VAPORS IN THE TRAILER AND BECAME MORE CONCERNED AND CALLED INTO OUR WEEKEND PAGER, ALSO SINCE HAD BEEN WORKING WITH VINCE WITH ONYX HE TRIED TO CALL HIM ON HIS CELL (VINCE'S) PHONE BUT WAS UNABLE TO REACH HIM.  TERRY CRAWFORD FROM OUR OFFICE IN WEST JORDAN RESPONDED TO JB'S PAGE AND ALSO TRIED TO CALL VINCE WITHOUT SUCCESS.  AFTER TALKING WITH THE DRIVER AND OBSERVING THE TRAILER TO THE EXTENT THAT WE COULD WITHOUT ENTERING THE TRAILER (BECAUSE OF THE VAPORS) THERE APPEARED TO BE NO EXTERNAL LEAKING, JUST INTERNAL CONDENSATION FROM THE VAPOR AND OPENING THE DOORS HAD TO AN EXTENT AIRED THE TRAILER.  IT WAS DECIDED THAT SINCE THERE WERE NO OBVIOUS LEAKS HE COULD PROCEED TO THE ONYX FACILITY WHERE THEY WOULD BE BETTER ABLE ACCESS THE POSSIBLE VENTING AND DEAL WITH THE CONDITION.  TWO ADDITIONAL STOPS IN ROUTE REVEALED NO EXTERNAL LEAKING.  SUNDAY MORNING JB MEET WITH ONYX EMPLOYEE AT THE HENDERSON FACILITY AND EXPLAINED THE SITUATION.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO TAKE THE TRAILER TO A CONTAINMENT AREA AND LEAVE IT AND WAS ASSURED THAT THE APPROPRIATE PEOPLE AT ONYX WOULD BE NOTIFIED.  JB RETURNED EARLY ON MONDAY MORNING FOR HIS SCHEDULED DELIVERY AND AGAIN INFORMED ONYX ABOUT THE CONDITION OF THE SHIPMENT, AN ONYX RESPONDER WAS SUITED UP AND ENTERED THE TRAILER, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS A POSSIBLE PACKAGING FAILURE AND EVENTUALLY JB WAS INSTRUCTED TO BACK THE TRAILER INTO THE DOCK AT THE ONYX PLANT, THE PALLETIZED PRODUCT WAS UNLOADED AND JB WAS RELEASED AND WENT HOME BUT THE TRAILER REMAINED TO BE CLEANED.  WE LATER LEARNED THAT AS THE DRUMS WERE BEING LIFTED OFF THE PALLET FOR OVER-PACKING THE BOTTOMS FAILED AND PRODUCT WAS RELEASED IN THE FACILITY, APPARENTLY THIS PRODUCT WAS REACTIVE.  ONYX HAS HAD RESPONDERS IN TO HANDLE THE CLEAN-UP OF THEIR FACILITY.  THE SHIPMENT IS BEING RELOADED ONTO ANOTHER SAVANNAH TRAILER AND WILL LEAVE TODAY FOR A FRIDAY DELIVERY IN EAST LIVERPOOL.
column169: INCIDENT REPORT SUPPLEMENTED BY JENNIFER EBERLE, TRANSPORTATION COMPLIANCE MANAGER, ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, LLC, 973-448-4209.  ADDED PACKAGE ID MARKING.

column168: JULY 25, 2005 VEHICLE ACCIDENT    TERRY BUTLER WAS DRIVING SOUTH ON I-405 AT MILE MARKER 26 TRAVELING 50 TO 52 MILES PER HOUR ON A CLEAR AFTERNOON AT 6:30 PMM IN A 1994 INTERNATIONAL CAB-OVER 10-WHEEL BOX TRUCK WITH TWO OTHER PASSENGERS.  TERRY WAS HAULING 6155 LBS OF 1.5D EXPLOSIVES, 495 LBX OF 1.1D EXPLOSIVES AND 205 EACH 1.4B DETONATORS IN AN IME-22 BOX.    TERRY SAY TRAFFICE MERGING ONTO 1-405 FOMR THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY OFF SR 527 AND SIGNALED A LANE CHANGE AND MOVED INTO THE LEFT LANE.  AFTER TERRY COMPLETED THE LANE CHANGE HE LOOKED DOWN TO TURN OFF THE TURN SIGNAL AND WHEN HE RETURNED HIS EYES TO THE HIGHWAY HE SAW A LINE OF STOPPED OR VERY SLOW MOVING VEHICLES DIRECTLY IN FRONT OF HIM.  TERRY APPLIED THE BRAKES ATTEMPTING TO STOP.  THE LAST VEHICLE IN THE LINE OF STOPPED VEHICLES A 1989 TOYOTA CAMRY SAW THE TRUCK COMING AND BEGAN TO CHANGE LANES TO THE RIGHT.  BEFORE THE TOYOTA WAS ABLE TO COMPLETE THE LANE CHANGE TERRY STRUCK THE TOYOTA IN THE LEFT REAR CORNER WITH THE RIGHT FRONT CORNER OF THE INTERNATIONAL.    AFTER CONTACT THE TOYOTA SHOT ACROSS THE RIGHT ALNE INTO THE GUARD RAIL COMING TO A STOP AND THE INTERNATIONAL THAT TERRY WAS DRIVING SPUN TO THE RIGHT AND SKIDDING LEFT TURNING OVER ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE VEHICLE STOPPING IN THE RIGHT LANE.    BOTH DRIVERS AND THE TWO PASSENGERS IN THE INTERNATIONAL WERE UN-INJURED IN THE ACCIDENT.  THE HIGWAY REMAINED OPEN FOLLOWING THE ACCIDENT UNTIL DYNO NOBEL WAS ABLE TO TRANSFER A SECOND VEHICLE OT THE ACCIDENT AND A TWO VEHICLE WAS AT TEH ACCIDENT SITE.  AFTER BOTH THE TOW VEHICLE AND THE DYNO NOBEL VEHICLE WERE IN PLACE THE HIGWAY WAS CLOSED, PRODUCT TRANSFERRED AND THE ACCDIENT VEHICLE ROLLED BACK ON ITS WHEELS.  THE AMOUNT OF TIME THAT THE HIGHWAY WAS CLOSED WAS APPROXIMATELY 45 MINUTES.  NO PRODUCT WAS SPILLED, PACKAGES BROKE OPEN OR FUEL SPILLED FOMR THE VEHICLE SO NO CLEANUP WAS REQUIRED.

ON JULY 9TH, 2005, AT APPROXIMATELY 5:30 PM (CDT) MR. VALDIMIR VOYEVODSKIY WAS PULLING A 53 FT DRY VAN WITH 34,116 LBS OF SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION IN 12 LIQUID CARRYING "TOTES" AND 7,762 LBS OF CLEANING COMPOUNDS IN 3 DRUMS.  MR. VOYEVODSKIY WAS EXITING WESTBOUND ON I-215 S AND ENTERING SOUTHBOUND I-15 RAMP.  THE SPEED LIMIT WAS 25 MPH.  MR. VOYEVODSKIY STATES THAT HE WAS TRAVELING AROUND 20 - 25 MPH.  THE RAMP BETWEEN THE TWO INTERSTATE HIGHWAYS IS A TIGHT "CLOVERLEAF" TURN AND AS MR. VOYEVODSKIY STARTED INTO THE TURN THE LIQUID IN THE "TOTES" STARTED TO SHIFT AND WHEN THE TRUCK WENT INTO THE SHARP TURN THE CARGO SHIFTED TO THE LEFT AS HE WAS MAKING A RIGHT LOOP, AND THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER ONTO ITS LEFT SIDE ON THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT (SHOULDER) AND THE GRASS EMBANKMENT.  THE HIGHWAY PATROL, FIRE DEPARTMENT, HAZARDOUS RESPONSE TEAM, AND LOCAL LAW ENFORCEMENT WERE CALLED TO THE SCENE.  THE CONTAINER HOLDING THE ABOVE REFERENCED PRODUCT STARTED TO LEAK FROM THEIR FILL POINTS AND A COUPLE FROM CRACKED OR SPLIT SEAMS.  THE COMPANY THAT WAS CALLED OUT TO RECOVER THE CARGO, TW COMPANY, FOUND MOST OF THE CONTAINERS WERE LEAKING OR WERE SITUATED IN A POSITION THAT THEY WERE UNABLE TO UNLOAD THEM WITHOUT RELEASING MORE OF THE PRODUCT.  CONSEQUENTLY, THEY HAD TO PUNCTURE THE BOTTOM OF THE "TOTES" AND BARRELS TO EXTRACT THE LIQUID.  IN DOING SO THE SODIUM HYDROXIDE AND THE CLEANING SOLUTION BECAME MIXED TOGETHER IN THEIR CARGO TANK AND THUS BECAOME A HAZARDOUS WASTE THAT HAD TO BE DISPOSED OF.  THERE WAS NO RECORD KEPT OF WHICH CONTAINERS RUPTURED OR LEAKED AS TW COMPANY EXTRACTED THE CHEMICALS.  HOWEVER THE TIME OF DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS OVER A PERIOD OF ABOUT FOUR HOURS.  THE HAZ-MAT RESPONSE TEAM CONTAINED THE LIQUID THAT DID LEAK OUT DURING THAT TIME UNTIL TW COMPANY ARRIVED TO START THE CLEANUP PROCESS.  THE MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED AND DISPOSED OF AT CLEAN HARBORS GRASSY MOUNTAIN FACILITY IN GRASSY MOUNTAIN, UT.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS BROUGHT IN FOR ADDITIONAL TRAINING ON THE EXITING AND ENTERING OF HIGHWAYS AND THE RECOGNITION OF DANGEROUS SETTING (I.E.: SHARP CURVES, RAMP, ETC.) WHEN HAULING LIQUID CARGO.  THE DRIVER HAS HAULED DRY GOODS PRIMARILY AND WAS UNFAMILIAR WITH THE DYNAMICS OF LIQUID TRANSPORT.  THIS ISSUES WAS REVIEWED WITH HIM.  IT WAS AGREED UPON THAT IN THE FUTURE THE DRIVER WOULD CONTACT THE J&H TRUCKING SAFETY OFFICE FOR REVIEW OF PROCEDURES WHENEVER HE IS DISPATCHED ON LOADS OF LIQUID CARGO, REGARDLESS OF IT BEING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS OR NOT.  THIS WILL GIVE HIM OPPORTUNITY TO REVIEW SAFETY PROCEDURES AND THE PRECAUTIONS NEEDED FOR LIQUID CARGO TRANSPORT.

SPILL TECHNICIANS MATTHEW GROSVENOR AND KENNETH OPPY DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE AND EMITTING AN ODOR.  THEY REMOVED THE PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION. THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED INTO WILMINGTON VIA FLIGHT # 1644.  THIS SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE MARKINGS/LABELS OR A SHIPPERS DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THIS WAS A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.
